in a simple language in order to ensure that they reach out effectively and can be agreed upon by all denominations. We were also keen on integrating Biblical principles and verses with scientific knowledge in a simple manner that makes the study accessible to unspecialized researchers. At the same time, we hope that we have included enough depth to benefit the more specialized reader. How should the lessons be used? The lessons could be used in the form of sermons or lectures. They can further be used in personal and group studies. Numerous prayers are also included; we suggest believers and", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "c8b023cf-bc00-4d70-b330-4334933bf896": {"__data__": {"id_": "c8b023cf-bc00-4d70-b330-4334933bf896", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-guide-responding-hiv-christian-ministers-pastors-and-communities", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "A Pacific Guide on Responding to HIV for Christian Ministers, Pastors and Communities", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-guide-responding-hiv-christian-ministers-pastors-and-communities", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "5e81f2d5d1ac779be0d834fac9f8bdcbc3dbcac4c518c8572b2233fb36dec697"}}, "hash": "5e81f2d5d1ac779be0d834fac9f8bdcbc3dbcac4c518c8572b2233fb36dec697", "text": "religious leaders use these in quiet times or in public prayers. We ask the Lord Jesus Christ to use these lessons for the glory of His blessed name and for the extension of His kingdom. We pray that a helping hand would bring heavenly love and reach out to those who suffer and are vulnerable to the dangers of the pandemic throughout the world. Breaking the Silence 2 \u201cSon of man, prophesy against the shepherds of Israel; prophesy and say to them: \u2018This is what the Sovereign LORD says: Woe to the shepherds of Israel who only take care of themselves! Should not shepherds take care of the flock? 3 You eat the curds, clothe yourselves with the wool and slaughter the choice animals, but you do not take care of the flock. 4 You have not strengthened the weak or healed the sick or bound up the injured. You have not brought back the strays or searched for the lost. You have ruled them harshly and brutally. 5 So they were scattered because there was no shepherd, and when they were scattered they became food for all the wild animals\u2026.11 \u201c \u2018For this is what the Sovereign LORD says: I myself will search for my sheep and look after them.\u201d (Ezekiel 34: 2-5, 11)1 A Quick Introduction to HIV and AIDS \u2022 HIV [Human Immunodeficiency Virus]. HIV is the virus which can lead to AIDS. HIV reduces your body\u2019s immunities so they have more difficulty fighting off diseases. The immune system can never fully get rid of HIV because the virus attacks the immune system itself--the very thing that would normally get rid of a virus. \u2022 AIDS [Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndrome]. AIDS is a syndrome, a collection of signs and conditions resulting from low immunity tolerance which is signified by the presence of specific health conditions called opportunistic infections. These infections are caused by microbes such as viruses or bacteria that usually do not make healthy people sick. Some of these infections include Lymphoma (& other specific cancers), Candidiasis, recurrent Pneumonia, Dementia, Tuberculosis etc. 1All scriptural quotations are taken from the New International Version unless otherwise indicated Lesson One: A message to the pastors and ministers of the Church As a medical problem and from the aspect of the economy, AIDS is no doubt all bad news! But from a moral point of view, it does not need to be all bad news; through its challenge, it has the potential to make us all better human beings. (Tonga\u2019s Bishop Finau launching the SPC\u2019s Pacific Islands AIDS and STD Prevention Project in 1990) Themes: Breaking the silence A Quick Introduction to HIV and AIDS HIV and AIDS in the Pacific The importance of awareness and caution Messages we need to convey The value of the ailing Our mission as ministers of Christ Guideline for Christian Leaders Guideline for Christian Leaders 8 9 \u2022 Some people refer to \u201cHIV Disease\u201d but this is a terminology that can lead to confusion for many because we tend to think of \u201cdisease\u201d in simple terms: infection equals illness. It\u2019s a little different with HIV since the virus can cause slow, subtle damage to the immune system long before an infected person will feel ill. HIV is a continuum with different stages. Health care providers use the term \u201cHIV disease\u201d to identify the variety of changes a person may experience, from initial infection to more advanced stages of serious, life-threatening illness. The term describes the medical condition of anyone infected with the virus, regardless of his or her symptoms. How does HIV cause illnesses? HIV reproduces continuously in the body from the first day of infection. A person who is infected with HIV will typically produce about 10 billion new HIV particles each day, and about 2 billion virus-fighting immune system cells (CD4 T cells- are produced and destroyed). A person\u2019s immune system attacks HIV soon after infection and at first is able to clear a large amount of virus from the body every 24 hours. However, for each virus particle cleared, at least one new one is created. The body\u2019s initial, vigorous anti-HIV response creates a temporary equilibrium between immune cells and the virus that may last for months or years. Typically, a person will show no outward signs of illness during this time, except in some instances flu-like symptoms after the initial infection as a sign that the immune system is kicking-in to fight off HIV. Over time, however, the virus gains the upper hand. The amount of HIV in the body (viral load) increases and the CD4 T cell", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "535c93f1-ea7b-4bb7-a0bb-0261fb07ea3b": {"__data__": {"id_": "535c93f1-ea7b-4bb7-a0bb-0261fb07ea3b", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-guide-responding-hiv-christian-ministers-pastors-and-communities", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "A Pacific Guide on Responding to HIV for Christian Ministers, Pastors and Communities", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-guide-responding-hiv-christian-ministers-pastors-and-communities", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e419d5c6bab4edf2f2088662179818a4129f4f6136d78cc2c42f2812dd09e650"}, "3": {"node_id": "537f42f2-0d67-4685-9022-da8eec7eba68", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-guide-responding-hiv-christian-ministers-pastors-and-communities", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "d2d4656cddeb6acb14c562d120ea7bd8e295b0e287226a7d2340a0e707b77783"}}, "hash": "cb59f1753bea2d7d2837a11e9257555815800e2ce0cfdd02d53c5467d55dd8c7", "text": "count declines. The immune system cannot work properly under constant attack from HIV. Eventually, the virus overwhelms the defenses of the immune system, which then can no longer ward off other illness-causing infections, some of which can be life threatening. How is HIV transmitted? The virus is present in certain bodily fluids and can be passed from one infected individual to another through: \u2022 Blood (including menstrual blood) \u2022 Semen (pre-cum) \u2022 Vaginal secretions \u2022 Breast milk The HIV virus is not easily transmitted. It depends on the amount of virus present in these bodily fluids which actually varies with the stage of infection. It is highest at the early stage of infection, decreases slightly during the long symptoms-free period and increases dramatically at the AIDS stage. The most \u2018infectious\u2019 bodily fluid is blood. Studies have shown that infection rates are generally higher for male-to-male transmission and needle sharing. Transmission is about twice as high from male-to-female than from female-to-male. The virus is more likely to be transmitted during certain sex acts where mucous membranes are more easily broken than during other sex acts where the mucous membranes are more likely to remain intact. The presence of other Sexually Transmitted Infections, particularly those who form lesions and ulcers on the genitals is a facilitating factor for HIV transmission. People living with HIV who are taking their anti-retroviral treatment correctly and consistently have low level of virus (sometimes almost undetectable) present in their bodily fluids and thus, they are very significantly less likely to transmit their virus to others compared to people not on treatment for example, even in the absence of preventative measure. Recent studies suggests that anti-retroviral treatment can reduce up to 96% the risk of transmission in couples where only one partner is infected with HIV. This represents a major breakthrough. As mentioned before, most HIV transmission in the world happen between people who ignore their HIV positive status (and therefore are not accessing treatment) and their sexual partners, husbands, wives, boyfriends, girlfriends and unborn children. Activities that can transmit HIV 3 Penetrative and unprotected sexual contact. 3 Direct blood contact/exchange, particularly through sharing injection drug needles. 3 Infections due to blood transfusions, accidents in health care settings or certain blood products are possible but tend to become very rare as universal precautions are routinely in place 3 Mother to baby (before or during birth, or through breast milk feeding) ANYONE that does not know his/her own HIV status, or the HIV status of his/her sexual partner(s), and or engages in any of the activities above can potentially be infected by the HIV virus or infect others if he or she is already and unknowingly infected. HIV is NOT spread by? 7 Air 7 Hugging 7 Kissing 7 Sharing clothes, food, utensils, water 7 Toilets, showers, swimming pools and other facilities 7 Insect bites (mosquitoes do not inject own or previously bitten person\u2019s blood into someone else). 7 Feces, saliva, sweat, tears, urine, or vomit 2 2For more information visit the following websites: http://www.globalhealthreporting.org/ diseaseinfo.asp?id=275, http://www.apla.org/facts/hiv101.html#not, http://www.aidsmap.com/How-is-HIV-transmitted/page/1443476/, http://www.unaids.ru/en/ initiatives/projects/friendship/, http://www.aids-india.org/hivbasics4.htm, http://www.healthexpertadvice.org/forum/STDs/How-likely-is-it-to-pass-AIDS-through-saliva-94283. htm, http://www.experts123.com/q/how-is-hiv-not-transmitted.html, http://www.thebody.com/h/ can-you-spread-hiv-through-kissing.html, http://www.themedicalquestions.com/illness/can-a- mosquito-spread-aids.html Guideline for Christian Leaders Guideline for Christian Leaders 10 11 How can one reduce HIV infection? 3 Good self-esteem and respect and care for others 3 Know your HIV status. If it is negative make sure it stays that way.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "537f42f2-0d67-4685-9022-da8eec7eba68": {"__data__": {"id_": "537f42f2-0d67-4685-9022-da8eec7eba68", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-guide-responding-hiv-christian-ministers-pastors-and-communities", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "A Pacific Guide on Responding to HIV for Christian Ministers, Pastors and Communities", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-guide-responding-hiv-christian-ministers-pastors-and-communities", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e419d5c6bab4edf2f2088662179818a4129f4f6136d78cc2c42f2812dd09e650"}, "2": {"node_id": "535c93f1-ea7b-4bb7-a0bb-0261fb07ea3b", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-guide-responding-hiv-christian-ministers-pastors-and-communities", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "cb59f1753bea2d7d2837a11e9257555815800e2ce0cfdd02d53c5467d55dd8c7"}}, "hash": "d2d4656cddeb6acb14c562d120ea7bd8e295b0e287226a7d2340a0e707b77783", "text": "If it is negative make sure it stays that way. If it is positive comply with your health care providers advice 3 Know your partners HIV status 3 Monogamy 3 Celibacy 3 Know how to use protection (male and female condoms) 3 Non-penetrative sex. Explore other ways to express intimacy that are not high risk. 3 Stay informed and always ask questions 3 Do not share needles or instruments that have been in contact with someone else\u2019s blood Testing for HIV The ONLY way to know if one is infected with HIV is to take an HIV test. The HIV test is one of the most accurate medical tests. More than 75% of people who are infected with HIV do not know that they are because they have not taken the test. HIV is mostly transmitted by people who do not know their HIV status. The HIV test looks for HIV antibodies in your body (this means the test actually looks at the response from your immune system to the virus). If you have HIV antibodies, your test results will be positive. This means you have HIV. If you don\u2019t have HIV antibodies, your test will be negative. This means one of two things: -You don\u2019t have HIV. -You have HIV, but your body hasn\u2019t made enough antibodies to", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "9165ab52-ee18-4c29-bf49-6bb74e2f2f79": {"__data__": {"id_": "9165ab52-ee18-4c29-bf49-6bb74e2f2f79", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-guide-responding-hiv-christian-ministers-pastors-and-communities", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "A Pacific Guide on Responding to HIV for Christian Ministers, Pastors and Communities", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-guide-responding-hiv-christian-ministers-pastors-and-communities", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "59f9628d8d325adec385f59be51eee7489e88c6374f16a0e939268eb7e2c68f7"}}, "hash": "59f9628d8d325adec385f59be51eee7489e88c6374f16a0e939268eb7e2c68f7", "text": "be detected yet It can take up to 3 months and exceptionally up to 6 months (but it is usually as early as 3-4 weeks) after initial infection for the body to make HIV antibodies. This period during which the antibodies are not detectable is called the Window Period. That is why it is When an antibody test is found positive, a confirmatory test using a different type of test is performed to double check. HIV Treatment: Antiretroviral Therapy (ART) There are neither known cures nor vaccine for HIV yet but a range of drugs have been developed and are used in combination to avoid resistance by the virus. These drugs referred to as antiretroviral drugs or ARVs do not completely kill the virus but they significantly slow down its progression and reduce the amount of virus circulating in the body (viral load) and thus allows for the immune system to recover. Therapy using ARVs is referred to as ART (AntiRetroviral Therapy). People taking ART are committed to a lifelong treatment. Thanks to ART, HIV is no longer a death sentence and people infected with HIV can live long and productive lives. Most countries provide ART free of charge. Increasingly new drugs are being developed that are more effective and have fewer side effects. When people are taking ARVs it is very important that they adhere to their doctor\u2019s prescription otherwise the virus may become resistant to the drugs. As mentioned above people on therapy have significantly reduced chances to transmit their virus to their long term sexual partners due to their reduced viral load. And it is to be noted that generally HIV is transmitted to others by people who ignore their HIV positive status. ART is also used to prevent the transmission of the virus from an infected mother to her infant. This is very effective and, along with other precautionary measures, it can virtually eliminate this mode of transmission. This is called Prevention of Parent to Child Transmission. HIV vulnerability: risk factors (\u201crisk behaviours\u201d) and drivers The term \u201crisk factors\u201d refers to aspects of personal behaviours or lifestyle, an environment exposure or an inborn or inherited characteristic, which on the basis of epidemiologic evidence is known to be associated with health-related condition(s).3 These include behaviours such as sharing needles for injecting drug use, unprotected casual sex and multiple concurrent partners over a long period of time with low and inconsistent condom use, rough and coerced sex, anal sex, etc\u2026. Because these particular behaviours carry a greater risk of HIV transmission or acquisition, they are often called \u201chigh risk behaviours\u201d. The term \u201cdrivers of HIV epidemic\u201d relates to the structural and social factors such as poverty, human rights violation, unequal access to information, income and opportunities and prominently gender inequality that increase people\u2019s vulnerability to HIV infection. These are not easily measured but account for the increase and maintenance of an HIV epidemic at the population level. \u201cDrivers\u201d at population level and risk factors at individual level are closely linked. Individual behaviours, sexual behaviour included, are shaped by the social environment in which individuals live, their degree of agency and gendered expectations and norms as defined by culture. Effective prevention efforts require action to understand and address the socio-economic and cultural realities in which behaviors are shaped. The assumption that education alone leads to behavior change is shortsighted. HIV and AIDS in the Pacific 4 After two decades of responding to HIV in the region, we still do not have consistent and reliable information about estimated levels and distribution of HIV, due to continuing poor surveillance and inadequate epidemiological data. The absence of biological and behavioural surveillance among specific groups limits understanding of who is at risk of HIV infection and the ability to target appropriate prevention strategies. The trends in the number of HIV cases detected is as much about changes in the availability and uptake of HIV testing as about real spread of HIV within and between countries. Conclusions on the basis of reported cases must be tentative and the true epidemiological picture of HIV in the region is still uncertain. Outside of Papua New Guinea, New Caledonia, French Polynesia, Guam and perhaps Fiji, the low number of reported cases makes it difficult to predict with any certainty the future growth of HIV in the region. Only a limited number of countries (most notably Papua New Guinea) undertake HIV estimates; most of the countries depend on reported cases for the planning of their national responses. 3John M. Last, editor, A dictionary of Epidemiology, 3rd edition (New York, Oxford University Press, 1995) 4 Sources: Report", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "4bd58be9-6e70-449b-8848-ce3f57fd7560": {"__data__": {"id_": "4bd58be9-6e70-449b-8848-ce3f57fd7560", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-guide-responding-hiv-christian-ministers-pastors-and-communities", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "A Pacific Guide on Responding to HIV for Christian Ministers, Pastors and Communities", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-guide-responding-hiv-christian-ministers-pastors-and-communities", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "8f54845657b29249cce3f30d258d92a79bcdec09a2f3ae7e1553d642adb8b5e4"}, "3": {"node_id": "bf037eba-293b-449c-b7a1-a29b64dd44f0", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-guide-responding-hiv-christian-ministers-pastors-and-communities", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "190d86120282132ccc81d56581875f4301e148e8fddb27bcfb66ce51702d3a56"}}, "hash": "1d290887283fc4b1bf7b0f34c13d219a6be7ad6b1857e6a86ed93bb2fb3caf48", "text": "of the Commission on AIDS in the Pacific, 2009, UNAIDS 2011, UNDP 2012 Guideline for Christian Leaders Guideline for Christian Leaders 12 13 Graph 1. Annual reported HIV cases by sub-region 1981-2009 (source SPC 2010) As at December 2011, the total cumulative reported HIV cases in the pacific including PNG is 33,218; 98 new HIV diagnoses were reported in 2011 for the Pacific excluding PNG. Cases from Papua New Guinea make up over 99% of reported cases in 2008. In Papua New Guinea there are 31,609 reported cases as at 2011, although UNAIDS estimates that the number of people living with HIV is 54,000. A similar level of under-reporting in the rest of the Pacific seems likely. Sub-regional trends over the past 25 years show a mixed picture with incidence increasing in Melanesia (driven by Fiji), relatively constant in Polynesia and decreasing in Micronesia from a peak in 1998-1999. The vast majority of people infected in the Pacific are young (19-35yrs old), the average age at HIV diagnosis being 30 years. The share of women and girls in the caseload has increased steadily. In PNG, 60% of new infections in 2007 were amongst women. Region- wide, women\u2019s share of the epidemic has increased from 20% in 1985 to 46% lately. This is consistent with predominantly heterosexual transmission but is also likely related to the fact that women are more tested then men (through Ante Natal Care). In small populations even a small number of people living with HIV can be devastating, particularly so when the most impacted are young productive adults. On the basis of the reported numbers of people living with HIV, the region can be categorized as follows: Papua New Guinea\u2014the overwhelming locus of the Pacific epidemic; Fiji, French Polynesia, New Caledonia and Guam\u2014 with significant HIV cases; and other countries, including the smaller island states\u2014where known cases are fewer. Sexual transmission is the predominant mode of transmission (95%) followed by vertical transmission (5-10%). The extent of male to male transmission is not well evidenced. It is believed to be underreported outside the French and US territories which exhibit significant proportions of infections due to male-male sex and injecting drug use. The share of MSM transmission for the region (PNG excluded) is tentatively 27%, largely driven by the territories mentioned above. Sexually Transmitted Infections (STIs) like chlamydia and syphilis are endemic across the region. The presence of STIs significantly increases the risk of contracting HIV if exposed to the virus. The high prevalence of common STIs (chlamydia, syphilis, gonorrhea, trichomoniasis, genital herpes) found in reproductive age groups across the PICs represent an important risk factor for HIV spread. Knowledge of reproductive health, STI signs and symptoms and health seeking behaviors for these highly stigmatized conditions (\u201cshame diseases\u201d) are very low as well as the use of preventative methods known to stop the transmission of STIs and HIV such as male and female condoms. Graph 2. Percentage of positive Chlamydia tests by sub-region in 2009 (Screening in asymptomatic patients vs diagnostic in symptomatic patients) Graph 3. Percentage of positive syphillis tests by sub-region in 2009 (Screening in asymptomatic patients vs diagnostic in symptomatic patients) Data source SPC Public Health Programme HIV and STI section 2010: Mobility of occupational groups susceptible to be more exposed to HIV (sex workers, soldiers, mobile men with money) is also well documented throughout the region. Seafarers have been noted as one of the highest priority risk group for HIV transmission and contribute disproportionately to the HIV caseload of Tuvalu (41%) and Kiribati (100%). Limited studies have found HIV prevalence between 6 and 14% amongst Port Moresby sex workers. Data from other countries and other occupational groups at higher exposure risk is lacking. Sex work (or prostitution) per se is concentrated in urban centers, ports and around development enclaves but transactional sex is common and widespread and often associated with alcohol abuse and low condom use. Limited studies have also found multiple concurrent sexual partnerships relatively common. Intergenerational sex is well documented in PNG (i.e young girls infected by older \u201csugar daddies\u201d men).", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "bf037eba-293b-449c-b7a1-a29b64dd44f0": {"__data__": {"id_": "bf037eba-293b-449c-b7a1-a29b64dd44f0", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-guide-responding-hiv-christian-ministers-pastors-and-communities", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "A Pacific Guide on Responding to HIV for Christian Ministers, Pastors and Communities", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-guide-responding-hiv-christian-ministers-pastors-and-communiti