", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-guide-responding-hiv-christian-ministers-pastors-and-communities", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ce03afb8875f048ca85b181f3940bc59625ab64fc28bd36e39579584ca329407"}}, "hash": "ce03afb8875f048ca85b181f3940bc59625ab64fc28bd36e39579584ca329407", "text": "Christian Leaders 14 15 The record high levels of gender-based and often sexual violence by an intimate partner (above 60% in Fiji and Solomon Islands, 40% in Samoa) pose direct and indirect disproportionate risk vulnerability to women, girls and transgendered persons. In PNG, studies have found that over 50% of women were forced into sex mostly by men known to them and 2 out of 3 wives reported being beaten by their husbands (a national average). Violence against women carries direct and indirect risk for HIV transmission. Women and girls who are victims of abuse are at heightened risk of infection. Gender inequality in custom, practice and law is a prominent vulnerability factor at population level and is believed to be the single most important contributing factor to the HIV epidemic in Papua New Guinea.5 HIV related social research in the Pacific Islands has highlighted the sub-optimal understandings of sexually transmitted infections signs and symptoms and sexual and reproductive health related issues among young (and older) people. Many Pacific Island cultures consider open discussion about sexuality across generations or in the public realm socially inappropriate. As the Fijian researcher Miliakere Kaitani notes about young Fijians \u201cknowledge is limited because they [young Fijians] have a narrow range of sources of information on sexuality and they are misinformed about this taboo topic. The end result is a high incidence of teenage pregnancy and high incidence of Sexually Transmitted Infections among the indigenous Fijian population\u201d.6 High level of stigma and discrimination and inadequate and discriminatory legal frameworks on the basis of gender or sexual orientation exacerbate the problem. Save for very few exceptions, most Pacific legislations criminalize sex work, homosexuality and HIV transmission. Few countries have laws that protect people living with HIV from discrimination and fewer (only Papua New Guinea, Pohnpei in Federated States of Micronesia and Fiji) have enacted comprehensive laws that integrate international human rights principles as they apply to HIV responses so far. The importance of warning signals and caution \u2022 Our church pulpits should send out a clarion call to warn the inattentive to the existing hazard. \u2022 Indications show that there is an increasing number of young people (including churchgoers) who are sexually active outside marriage. \u2022 Some people are ostracised because of their behaviours or lifestyle such as commercial sex workers and men who have sex with men. \u2022 As a result of stigmatization, social condemnation and the cruelness faced by these people, they are forced to hide; as a result prevention services do not reach them and HIV may spread unnoticed. Messages we need to convey The value of the ailing 26 Then God said, \u201cLet us make man in our image, in our likeness, and let them rule over the fish of the sea and the birds of the air, over the livestock, over all the earth, and over all the creatures that move along the ground.\u201d 27 So God created man in his own image, in the image of God he created him; male and female he created them. (Genesis 1:26-27) 19 Do you not know that your body is a temple of the Holy Spirit, who is in you, whom you have received from God? You are not your own; 20 you were bought at a price. Therefore honor God with your body. (1Corinth 6: 19-20) 8 But God demonstrates his own love for us in this: While we were still sinners, Christ died for us. (Romans 5:8) \u2022 Those living with or affected by HIV are still created in the image of God whether they are responsible for their condition or not. \u2022 The honour and pride of a nation is represented in the national flag. The morning salutation of the flag is a salutation of the nation. The flag is the image of the nation. \u2022 Man is the image of God. To love Man is to love God. \u2022 The sinner, the weak, the ailing and the broken, are still created in the image of God, hence their value is unlimited. \u2022 God demonstrated His love for us by sending His son to die on our behalf while we were yet sinners. \u2022 He still loves all sinners and calls upon them to enjoy His love. \u2022 Some heart patients, diabetics, hypertension patients and other patients are indeed responsible for their health conditions due to the frantic lifestyles they lead \u2013 for example through stress, overeating, smoking or lack of exercise. Undoubtedly, all such behaviour is sinful towards themselves and their bodies. \u2022 Some of those infected by HIV may be responsible for their condition because they", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "92e1dff9-ba87-4963-b325-fcf41f60dd42": {"__data__": {"id_": "92e1dff9-ba87-4963-b325-fcf41f60dd42", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-guide-responding-hiv-christian-ministers-pastors-and-communities", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "A Pacific Guide on Responding to HIV for Christian Ministers, Pastors and Communities", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-guide-responding-hiv-christian-ministers-pastors-and-communities", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "5172001299729d233384863810bf1ed3340d02cf5426154014b76a28ce6ce2e4"}}, "hash": "5172001299729d233384863810bf1ed3340d02cf5426154014b76a28ce6ce2e4", "text": "have behaved in a certain way which can rightfully be described as sinful. Yet despite From our pulpits we must declare that: 1. HIV exists among us. 2. God still loves, cares for and longs to pour His grace on those infected and affected by HIV. 3. Abstinence and faithfulness to one\u2019s spouse are the safest preventive measures to take. 4. God does not punish particular sins more than He does others. Rather, He calls upon all humans to repent, embrace holy love and lead a pure life. 5. We need to search for the lost, restore the castaway and bind the broken in spirit and soul. 6. We need to pray that the Lord would send out ministers to reach through to people who are most vulnerable to HIV, bringing forth His message of love, forgiveness, grace and power. 5\u201cGender and HIV in the Pacific Islands Region\u201d a Literature Review of Evidence with recommendations UNDP 2009 6Kaitani, Miliakere, \u201cBidging the Gap: the changing reproductive and sexual expectations of Fijian men.\u201d Ph.D. Thesis, Australian National University. 2003 Guideline for Christian Leaders Guideline for Christian Leaders 16 17 the fact that we do not condemn diabetics, or those suffering from hypertension or heart problems, we may very well condemn those infected or affected by HIV, reject them, fear them and isolate them. \u2022 This is not the message of Christ. Grave ailment - any grave ailment - is but a predicament that befalls the ailing and their families; yet, it is also an opportunity for spiritual growth \u2013 changing a lifestyle for the glory of Christ. \u2022 We have to declare a message of love and hope to those infected and affected by HIV from our pulpits and within our meetings. \u2022 We need to encourage those who think they may have been exposed to HIV to take the necessary blood test voluntarily; it is available free of charge in all Pacific Island countries. \u2022 We need to offer those affected and infected with HIV support, not hostility, love, not criticism, respect, not indifference. We need to show them the spirit of fraternity and not that of exclusion. \u2022 Those infected or affected by HIV may still come to be the \u201ctemple of God\u201d and a dwelling place for the Holy Spirit through repentance, faith in the Lord Jesus Christ and the cover of Christ the Saviour\u2019s blood. \u2022 We need to spread the message that the healthy might be cautious and the ailing might return to the arms of the Father to be covered and redeemed. Our mission as ministers of Christ 31 \u201cWhen the Son of Man comes in his glory, and all the angels with him, he will sit on his throne in heavenly glory. 32 All the nations will be gathered before him, and he will separate the people one from another as a shepherd separates the sheep from the goats. 33 He will put the sheep on his right and the goats on his left. 34 \u201cThen the King will say to those on his right, \u2018Come, you who are blessed by my Father; take your inheritance, the kingdom prepared for you since the creation of the world. 35 For I was hungry and you gave me something to eat, I was thirsty and you gave me something to drink, I was a stranger and you invited me in, 36 I needed clothes and you clothed me, I was sick and you looked after me, I was in prison and you came to visit me.\u2019 37 \u201cThen the righteous will answer him, \u2018Lord, when did we see you hungry and feed you, or thirsty and give you something to drink? 38 When did we see you a stranger and invite you in, or needing clothes and clothe you? 39 When did we see you sick or in prison and go to visit you?\u2019 40 \u201cThe King will reply, \u2018I tell you the truth, whatever you did fo