ers even sneered at him. They said, \u201cHe saved others; let him save himself if he is the Christ of God, the Chosen One.\u201d 36 The soldiers also came up and mocked him. They offered him wine vinegar 37 and said, \u201cIf you are the king of the Jews, save yourself.\u201d 38 There was a written notice above him, which read: THIS IS THE KING OF THE JEWS. Guideline for Christian Leaders Guideline for Christian Leaders 26 27 39 One of the criminals who hung there hurled insults at him: \u201cAren\u2019t you the Christ? Save yourself and us!\u201d 40 But the other criminal rebuked him. \u201cDon\u2019t you fear God,\u201d he said, \u201csince you are under the same sentence? 41 We are punished justly, for we are getting what our deeds deserve. But this man has done nothing wrong.\u201d 42 Then he said, \u201cJesus, remember me when you come into your kingdom.(Luke 23: 35-42) \u2022 The prayer that the thief prayed gave a meaning to his life in its entirety. \u2022 You may still have time in this life \u2013 be that short or long. \u2022 None of us knows exactly the time available for us on earth. \u2022 You need to fill every day you spend on earth in love for God and others. \u2022 Ask God that He may give you such love and show you how to exercise it in all that you say and do. \u2022 Do not fail to provide nurture, medication and good nutrition to your body. \u2022 Practice bodily exercise for it is profitable; and practice spiritual exercise and godliness for they are much more profitable. Caring for the body and the spirit 29 After all, no one ever hated his own body, but he feeds and cares for it, just as Christ does the church-- (Ephesians 5: 29) 8 For physical training is of some value, but godliness has value for all things, holding promise for both the present life and the life to come.(1 Timothy 4: 8) \u2022 Nurturing your body and fighting the ailment through medication, prayers, love and a balanced lifestyle is an expression of your faith and love for God. \u2022 Should your faith weaken or faint, seek power and help from the Lord. \u2022 Do not doubt your value as human, the value of your suffering, nor God\u2019s love for you. Should you doubt, ask the Lord to support the weakness in your faith. \u2022 Ask God to give you the power to face every hardship with dignity, joy and trust, as a child of God \u2013 a child of the King of Kings and Lord of Lords. \u2022 Ask Him to reveal in you all fruits of the Spirit, all health of the body, all faith and all trust of which He is the source. \u2022 Let not your heart be troubled, nor tremble away from God\u2019s love; His love will always lead you, even in the hardest and cruellest circumstances. Lesson Four: A message to families of people living with HIV Themes: Love for our ailing neighbour No need to avoid people living with HIV Are people living with HIV worse sinners than other people? Praying with and for the ailing Our perspective of people living with HIV Understanding the pain of the families of people living with HIV Ministering to our neighbours, people living with HIV Prayers for people living with HIV and their Families Love for our ailing neighbour 6 You see, at just the right time, when we were still powerless, Christ died for the ungodly. (Romans 5:", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "85f2e292-7a04-47a7-93ac-0afb2a9d3b17": {"__data__": {"id_": "85f2e292-7a04-47a7-93ac-0afb2a9d3b17", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-guide-responding-hiv-christian-ministers-pastors-and-communities", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "A Pacific Guide on Responding to HIV for Christian Ministers, Pastors and Communities", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-guide-responding-hiv-christian-ministers-pastors-and-communities", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c52423b8f010bab678338d4561581699885094eeaa8c04963aaa1cd02950fe20"}}, "hash": "c52423b8f010bab678338d4561581699885094eeaa8c04963aaa1cd02950fe20", "text": "6) We who are strong ought to bear with the failings of the weak and not to please ourselves. (Romans 15: 1) 8 If anyone does not provide for his relatives, and especially for his immediate family, he has denied the faith and is worse than an unbeliever.(1 Timothy 5: 8) 37 Jesus replied: \u201c \u2018Love the Lord your God with all your heart and with all your soul and with all your mind.\u2019 38 This is the first and greatest commandment. 39 And the second is like it: \u2018Love your neighbor as yourself.\u2019 (Matthew 22: 37-39) \u2022 The first and greatest command is to love God and every person we deal with. \u2022 Love is to offer help and try to build bridges of communication, understanding, listening and support. \u2022 Love is to provide care and concern, sparing no effort. \u2022 The Apostle Paul rebukes anyone who does not provide for his own household; he takes such to be denial of faith. \u2022 Upon realizing their HIV infection, a person is mostly subject to trauma and great stress - anticipating severe symptoms and ailments and eventually death. \u2022 Hence Man senses his own feebleness, incompetence and great need for strength. \u2022 The Bible states that Christ died for the feeble and not for the strong. The Apostle Paul asserts the fact that we are all dissolute, and as such Christ died for us. Therefore, regardless of the means of transmission, people living with HIV are so precious in the eyes of the Lord that He died for them. Guideline for Christian Leaders Guideline for Christian Leaders 28 29 No need to avoid people living with HIV We need to offer love and support to people living with HIV. This applies equally to those whose symptoms have appeared and those in whom there is not yet any indication of the symptoms. People living with HIV; are they worse sinners than other people? Now there were some present at that time who told Jesus about the Galileans whose blood Pilate had mixed with their sacrifices. 2 Jesus answered, \u201cDo you think that these Galileans were worse sinners than all the other Galileans because they suffered this way? 3 I tell you, no! But unless you repent, you too will all perish. 4 Or those eighteen who died when the tower in Siloam fell on them--do you think they were more guilty than all the others living in Jerusalem? 5 I tell you, no! But unless you repent, you too will all perish.\u201d (Luke 13: 1-5) \u2022 Some people living with HIV feel that their condition is an expression of God\u2019s disapproval; and some of them feel guilty because of their condition. Their families may sometimes feel the same way. \u2022 While the Lord Jesus was on earth, it was believed that the eighteen people killed when the tower of Siloam fell on them were worse sinners than others; similar beliefs existed about the Galilaeans, whose blood Pilate had mingled with their sacrifices. \u2022 People living with HIV are not worse sinners than the rest of the human race; we are all same when it comes to Divine balance (all fall short of the glory of God). \u2022 We may or may not know what caused the infection; but in all cases we need to trust in God\u2019s mercy, love and forgiveness. 24 and are justified freely by his grace through the redemption that came by Christ Jesus. (Romans 3: 24) \u2022 Some of the families of people living with HIV believe that it was the wrong behaviour of their sons or daughters that caused the infection. \u2022 They may feel that they have fallen short or have gone wrong in raising their children \u2013 not offering the right support to them. \u2022 There is no need to feel that way. It can very well be that we did not go wrong in raising our children, nor have we faltered in offering them support; and yet they become infected. \u2022 In fact, no one is without sin, and there is no sin worse than another. We should therefore not condemn our beloved ones or ourselves. HIV is not transmitted by: \u2022 Shaking hands \u2022 Hugging \u2022 Kissing \u2022 Saliva \u2022 Food utensils and bath equipment \u2022 Swimming pools \u2022 Everyday co-living \u2022 Sweat \u2022 Urine... Samantha\u2019s story Twenty-four year old Samantha lives in a village on the outskirts of Suva with her two young children. She was diagnosed HIV-positive in January 2007 when she was seven months pregnant with her youngest child. \u201cMy husband\u2019s a rugby player so he travels", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "d697c354-6ce3-42e1-90bc-c445254af7ad": {"__data__": {"id_": "d697c354-6ce3-42e1-90bc-c445254af7ad", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-guide-responding-hiv-christian-ministers-pastors-and-communities", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "A Pacific Guide on Responding to HIV for Christian Ministers, Pastors and Communities", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-guide-responding-hiv-christian-ministers-pastors-and-communities", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "03f3cf6644dd98fe1aec4a97ef83440bc53c29cd2589596743acb3227b70ced2"}}, "hash": "03f3cf6644dd98fe1aec4a97ef83440bc53c29cd2589596743acb3227b70ced2", "text": "around. His own family used to come and tell me that he was cheating on me and sleeping with other girls. I knew this was going on because sometimes he would get drunk with his friends and not come home until the next day,\u201d she says. \u201cWhen the doctor told me my results, all I wanted to do was kill myself,\u201d Samantha reflects. \u201cI knew I got it from my husband. He was the first and only guy I had slept with.\u201d Samantha hid her status from her family for the last two months of her pregnancy. \u201cI told my husband about my HIV test results. He wasn\u2019t even surprised. He just told me to \u2018pray hard\u2019 and \u2018don\u2019t think about it\u2019. Then I asked him to go for a test and he said no. That\u2019s when I knew that he already knew his status, and that he knew he was the one who had infected me.\u201d Samantha gave birth to a healthy baby boy who is HIV-negative. After a few months, she told her family about her HIV status - but only after rumours starting spreading. \u201cAt first, the village people didn\u2019t want to talk to me or come near me. So I kept to myself and just cried inside. When my mother asked me if the stories were true, I denied it at first but she knew. It was when I saw that she still would love me and support me that I broke down and told her everything.\u201d Now the whole village knows and supports her, after they also learnt how HIV is transmitted. Samantha separated from her husband a few months later. \u201cWhen I started to talk about the virus, he\u2019d tell me not to bring it up and to shut up,\u201d she said. \u201cHe beat me up and burned all my clothes and my daughter\u2019s clothes.\u201d Samantha now lives with her mother and children in the village. She goes fishing and sells the fish to feed her family. And she believes she has changed for the better. \u201cBefore, I was very stubborn and carefree. Now I have learnt to listen to others and have a heart, and not judge them.\u201d Source: Renagi Taukarai, PIAF (Pacific Islands AIDS Foundation) HIV can be transmitted through: Contact with blood, seminal and vaginal fluids, breast milk \u2013 should there be a lesion or cut in the skin or the mucous membranes though with the virus may enter the body. HIV infection occurs only through unsafe sex with an infected partner or through a wound caused by a sharp device contaminated with infected blood. There is therefore no need to shun or isolate people living with HIV Guideline for Christian Leaders Guideline for Christian Leaders 30 31 Praying with and for people living with HIV 16 Therefore confess your sins to each other and pray for each other so that you may be healed. The prayer of a righteous man is powerful and effective. (James 5: 16) 19 \u201cAgain, I tell you that if two of you on earth agree about anything you ask for, it will be done for you by my Father in heaven.20 For where two or three come together in my name, there am I with them.\u201d (Matthew 18: 19-20) \u2022 We need to pray with and for people living with HIV. \u2022 Christ promised a special power where believers identify with one another. \u2022 He further promised to be present in our midst as we gather to pray in His name. \u2022 Praying with people living with HIV provides them with special hope and power. Even if you are not used to praying together, you may just need to try; either use your church prayer books, or simply improvise. \u2022 Let us try to pray together or ask a church minister to join us in prayer. Our perspective of people living with HIV \u2022 People living with HIV, whether their symptoms have appeared or not, are not a source of danger, nor are they a cause of panic and terror. As we mentioned before, HIV is not transmitted by water, air or everyday co-living. \u2022 We should not avoid, shun or fear people living with HIV. Likewise we should not treat them as weird nor make them feel that they have committed a crime or an obscene act which deserves punishment. Neither should we show them pity or sympathy in a haughty manner; nor make them feel as if they are little children, or that they are impaired. \u2022 We need to remember that our infected beloved one is the very same son,", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "b57cc310-a696-4973-995b-3ed6662fd981": {"__data__": {"id_": "b57cc310-a696-4973-995b-3ed6662fd981", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-guide-responding-hiv-christian-ministers-pastors-and-communities", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "A Pacific Guide on Responding to HIV for Christian Ministers, Pastors and Communities", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-guide-responding-hiv-christian-ministers-pastors-and-communities", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "dc113bb3ae14c119055ecbae3b1d36022fff71f97977f5319577debbec6e94ac"}}, "hash": "dc113bb3ae14c119055ecbae3b1d36022fff71f97977f5319577debbec6e94ac", "text": "daughter, mother, sister or father whom we have loved and known all our lives. \u2022 People living with HIV are human beings with dignity and value; they are indeed worthy of our love and respect. Understanding the pain of the families of people living with HIV \u2022 Knowing that a beloved one is infected or affected with HIV causes great pain to family members. \u2022 This pain stems from fear of the infection and the stigma associated with it. \u2022 The grief in anticipation of the emotional and physical pain they will face. \u2022 The pain of confusion and not knowing when the symptoms will appear and when the end will come. 9 In all their distress he too was distressed, and the angel of his presence saved them. In his love and mercy he redeemed them; he lifted them up and carried them all the days of old.(Isaiah 63: 9) 15 For we do not have a high priest who is unable to sympathize with our weaknesses, but we have one who has been tempted in every way, just as we are--yet was without sin. (Hebrews 4: 15) 32 When Mary reached the place where Jesus was and saw him, she fell at his feet and said, \u201cLord, if you had been here, my brother would not have died.\u201d 33 When Jesus saw her weeping, and the Jews who had come along with her also weeping, he was deeply moved in spirit and troubled. 34 \u201cWhere have you laid him?\u201d he asked. \u201cCome and see, Lord,\u201d they replied. 35 Jesus wept. 36 Then the Jews said, \u201cSee how he loved him!\u201d 37 But some of them said, \u201cCould not he who opened the eyes of the blind man have kept this man from dying?\u201d (John 11: 32-37) \u2022 The Lord Jesus was deeply moved and troubled by the ailments of the people. \u2022 Jesus was troubled by the grief and predicaments of the people. Jesus, the knight, who was to soon strike a harsh blow to His greatest enemy, death, was troubled before the tomb of Lazarus; He even wept, right before He cried out loud, \u201cLazarus come forth.\u201d \u2022 Jesus Christ, the resurrection and the life, is troubled and weeps before disease and death. \u2022 The Lord is present in a special way and sends His angel to help the afflicted \u2013 the angel of His presence. \u2022 We pray that the Lord will open our eyes in time of confusion and pain in order that we might be in touch with Him and the wonderful angel of His presence. \u2022 The Lord Jesus gives us trust and hope in life eternal; likewise He gives us power and courage when He senses we are in the middle of pain and confusion. He was, like us, tempted in everything so that He would identify with the ailing and their families. \u2022 Does it amaze us that Jesus said that if we visited the ailing and treated them with love, that we would be doing the same to Jesus in person? (Matthew 25: 31-46). \u2022 Does it amaze us that the Lord of glory said that if we neglect or mistreat the ailing, we would be mistreating the Lord Jesus in person? Wonder, did Jesus mean to speak only of the righteous or the saints as He spoke of the ailing, or did he mean all of the ailing? Are not all the ailing sinners too? Ministering to our neighbours, people living with HIV \u2022 Whatever causes the infection of people living with HIV, they are all a reflection of the image of the Lord Jesus; when we serve and love them, we are indeed serving and loving the Lord Jesus in person. \u2022 Remember what the old man Simeon said to the Virgin Mary in his prophecy about the life and death of her beloved son. 35 so that the thoughts of many hearts will be revealed. And a sword will pierce your own soul too.\u201d (Luke 2:35). \u2022 The same message goes for the families of people living with HIV - a sword pierces through their souls. \u2022 However, they too, like the Virgin Mary, enjoy blessings and opportunities to experience the presence of the Lord, should they endure and accept the pain with power, courage and faith. \u2022 We pray for people living with HIV, their families and beloved ones; we will minister to them much like the Virgin Mary ministered to Elizabeth as the latter was pregnant with John the Baptist. Guideline for Christian Leaders Guideline for Christian Leaders 32 33 Prayers for people", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "4dee7bd6-a226-485d-8ef8-b439dc44be3e": {"__d