22 We pray that God would give us the wisdom to know the difference between the things that we can and the things that we cannot change. Lesson Five: A message to those surrounding people living with HIV Themes: Love, don\u2019t fear people living with HIV No need to isolate people living with HIV Treat people living with HIV with respect and equality Encourage people living with HIV to attend church regularly Love, don\u2019t fear people living with HIV 27 He answered: \u201c \u2018Love the Lord your God with your strength and with all your mind\u2019; and, \u2018Love your neighbor as yourself.\u2019 \u201c 28 \u201cYou have answered correctly,\u201d Jesus replied. \u201cDo this and you will live.\u201d 29 But he wanted to justify himself, so he asked Jesus, \u201cAnd who is my neighbor?\u201d 30 In reply Jesus said: \u201cA man was going down from Jerusalem to Jericho, when he fell into the hands of robbers. They stripped him of his clothes, beat him and went away, leaving him half dead.31 A priest happened to be going down the same road, and when he saw the man, he passed by on the other side. 32 So too, a Levite, when he came to the place and saw him, passed by on the other side. 33 But a Samaritan, as he traveled, came where the man was; and when he saw him, he took pity on him. 34 He went to him and bandaged his wounds, pouring on oil and wine. Then he put the man on his own donkey, took him to an inn and took care of him. 35 The next day he took out two silver coins and gave them to the innkeeper. \u2018Look after him,\u2019 he said, \u2018and when I return, I will reimburse you for any extra expense you may have.\u2019 36 \u201cWhich of these three do you think was a neighbor to the man who fell into the hands of robbers?\u201d 37 The expert in the law replied, \u201cThe one who had mercy on him.\u201d Jesus told him, \u201cGo and do likewise.\u201d (Luke 10: 27-37) \u2022 The Lord Jesus teaches us that every person we meet or may have contact with is our neighbour; His command to us is: \u201clove your neighbour as yourself.\u201d \u2022 The man who was wounded and was half dead needed the love of the Good Samaritan; and the Samaritan offered him that love. \u2022 People living with HIV need that same kind of love. \u2022 Perhaps the priest and Levite who passed by on the other side were scared to stop and help the man who was stripped, beaten and robbed, lest they face the same fate. In general, however, this fear is not justified. No need to isolate people living with HIV \u2022 Some people fear those infected or affected with HIV without justification. Unlike the \u2018flu, for example, HIV is not transmitted through food utensils, bath equipment, shaking hands, kissing or everyday co-living. There is therefore, no reason to isolate, avoid or fear people living with HIV. Guideline for Christian Leaders Guideline for Christian Leaders 34 35 \u2022 HIV is transmitted through blood, surgical equipment, sharp tools, syringes or unsafe sex. These are the only means of transmitting HIV. \u2022 Sharing the same Cup of Communion with people living with HIV presents absolutely no danger of infection, regardless of the way the sacrament is practiced. \u2022 We should express our love and support to all suffering people (especially people living with HIV); we should invite them", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "68acea55-f7a4-42b8-9ba5-ad3487a96265": {"__data__": {"id_": "68acea55-f7a4-42b8-9ba5-ad3487a96265", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-guide-responding-hiv-christian-ministers-pastors-and-communities", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": 