? 8 If you really keep the royal law found in Scripture, \u201cLove your neighbor as yourself,\u201d you are doing right. 9 But if you show favoritism, you sin and are convicted by the law as lawbreakers. 10 For whoever keeps the whole law and yet stumbles at just one point is guilty of breaking all of it. (James 2: 1-10) \u2022 The Lord instructs us to honour the successful and those who fail, the rich and the poor, the well and the sick \u2013 all in the same manner. \u2022 Excluding, isolating or disrespecting the ailing, those who are perceived to having fail, or those judge as sinners, is itself a sin worthy of rebuke and we should repent of it. \u2022 We need to receive people living with HIV into our churches and meetings with the same respect and honour with which we would treat anybody else. Encourage people living with HIV to attend church regularly 24 And let us consider how we may spur one another on toward love and good deeds. 25 Let us not give up meeting together, as some are in the habit of doing, but let us encourage one another--and all the more as you see the Day approaching. (Hebrews 10: 24-25) \u2022 Some people living with HIV choose to isolate themselves and stop attending church or spiritual gatherings. \u2022 The word of God commands us to encourage them to participate in good deeds and acts of love; and not to quit spiritual gatherings and meetings. \u2022 There is no justifiable reason - neither medical nor based on faith - to cause those infected or affected by HIV to isolate themselves or to stop attending spiritual fellowship and meetings. \u2022 On the contrary, people living with HIV should be encouraged to take advantage of the spiritual support and prayers offered by others. 14 And we urge you, brothers, warn those who are idle, encourage the timid, help the weak, be patient with everyone. (1 Thessalonians 5: 14). 10 \u201cSee that you do not look down on one of these little ones. For I tell you that their angels in heaven always see the face of my Father in heaven. \u201cFor the Son of man came to save the lost.\u201d (Matthew 18: 10-11) \u2022 People living with HIV may feel guilty, depressed or afraid. Some of them may even feel inferior to other people. \u2022 Some of them may be new in faith or have just started their spiritual journey. \u2022 We need to remember that the Son of Man has come to save that which was lost. \u2022 Our duty is to be determined to support, help and encourage anyone who feels inferior. Guideline for Christian Leaders Guideline for Christian Leaders 36 37 Lesson Six: What is your role as a minister towards people living with HIV and vulnerable groups? Themes: Breaking the silence Reaching out to vulnerable groups No condemnation Protecting the lives of those in danger Care and treatment for people living with HIV A prayer that the Lord would send us", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "ed49c45e-de69-4461-89a8-e724b92ccde3": {"__data__": {"id_": "ed49c45e-de69-4461-89a8-e724b92ccde3", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-guide-responding-hiv-christian-ministers-pastors-and-communities", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "A Pacific Guide on Responding to HIV for Christian Ministers, Pastors and Communities", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-guide-responding-hiv-christian-ministers-pastors-and-communities", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "6872ad39411e0903fead110dc6af0ccb5a4f3bd1c503e1b85b4dc2f8f1f2a362"}}, "hash": "6872ad39411e0903fead110dc6af0ccb5a4f3bd1c503e1b85b4dc2f8f1f2a362", "text": "out to minister \u201cYoung gay prostitutes in Fiji\u201d Many young men end up on the streets because of their sexual orientation, disowned by their family for being a homosexual, or finding few other doors open because they are inadequately educated. One young man said: \u201cI am 23-years old. I started doing this when I was 17. I have three sisters and two brothers and my family did not accept what I was becoming. I left home because I could not be myself, could not express myself and do things I was comfortable with. This job that I have guarantees that I pay my rent and buy my food. Sadly, now that I am on the streets, I am not being accepted by my family. But this is what I do now and I intend to do this for a while. These earnings also allow me to help my family during emergencies.\u201d While money is the driving force, some young men are there by choice, such as the son of a senior civil servant. In his home, homosexuality is abhorred. Selling sex is the only way he can find male partners. \u201cI don\u2019t know what they will do if I get seen out here. They give me money but I also want to enjoy myself,\u201d he said. And as if to justify his actions, he said, \u201cWell, we also have students here, high school students who come to make money to pay for school fees.\u201d Source: Fiji Times, 16 Nov 2008. The word of the LORD came to me: 2 \u201cSon of man, speak to your countrymen and say to them: \u2018When I bring the sword against a land, and the people of the land choose one of their men and make him their watchman, 3 and he sees the sword coming against the land and blows the trumpet to warn the people, 4 then if anyone hears the trumpet but does not take warning and the sword comes and takes his life, his blood will be on his own head. 5 Since he heard the sound of the trumpet but did not take warning, his blood will be on his own head. If he had taken warning, he would have saved himself. 6 But if the watchman sees the sword coming and does not blow the trumpet to warn the people and the sword comes and takes the life of one of them, that man will be taken away because of his sin, but I will hold the watchman accountable for his blood.\u2019 (Ezekiel 33: 1-6) Breaking the Silence \u2022 With the existence of at least 30,000 people infected with HIV in Oceania, the issue is one which affects us all. \u2022 We need to speak out about the presence of HIV among us, stating the basic facts of the pandemic from our church pulpits, schools, study groups and prayer meetings. \u2022 We need to encourage and organize campaigns to reach out to vulnerable people, particularly those that society marginalises through judgemental attitudes: commercial sex workers (prostitutes) and their clients, gay men and transgender persons, injecting drug users, women and girls who are victims of violence and perpetrators of this violence. Reaching out to vulnerable groups 18 Then Jesus came to them and said, \u201cAll authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me. 19 Therefore go and make disciples of all nations, baptizing them in the name of the Father and of the Son and of the Holy Spirit, 20 and teaching them to obey everything I have commanded you. And surely I am with you always, to the very end of the age.\u201d (Matthew 28: 18-20) 15 He said to them, \u201cGo into all the world and preach the good news to all creation (Mark 16: 15). 17 On hearing this, Jesus said to them, \u201cIt is not the healthy who need a doctor, but the sick. I have not come to call the righteous, but sinners.\u201d (Mark 2: 17). \u2022 Our aim should be to reveal the Love of God to those whom society rejects. \u2022 This rejection results in these people exposing themselves and -often unknowingly- others to danger. For example, a man who practices unprotected sex with commercial sex workers could be infected and then transmit the virus to other sex workers and to his wife, who might consequently transmit it to her infant baby. \u2022 An injecting drug user who uses a contaminated syringe may likewise transmit the virus to his wife. \u2022 Women, boys and girls who are victims of sexual violence in the family are at heightened risk", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "16a81e51-5576-4f08-8fa4-bbca4c4e4f2a": {"__data__": {"id_": "16a81e51-5576-4f08-8fa4-bbca4c4e4f2a", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-guide-responding-hiv-christian-ministers-pastors-and-communities", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "A Pacific Guide on Responding to HIV for Christian Ministers, Pastors and Communities", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-guide-responding-hiv-christian-ministers-pastors-and-communities", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "d7d00f2469f94bae50dbb5132692dddc0bfd5a7e07b6178c39fc107b014f1586"}}, "hash": "d7d00f2469f94bae50dbb5132692dddc0bfd5a7e07b6178c39fc107b014f1586", "text": "of contracting HIV directly from the perpetrators of the violence; and indirectly through their own risky behaviours they may subsequently engage in as the result of the loss of their self-esteem. Guideline for Christian Leaders Guideline for Christian Leaders 38 39 \u2022 Condemning, stigmatizing and isolating people who are vulnerable to HIV infection only fuels the spread of the pandemic in secret. \u2022 We must reach out to these people with love and sincerity and work on building relationships with them. \u2022 Condemning and isolating those infected or affected by HIV, will lead to their seclusion. This might even result in them seeking desperate actions that may put themselves and others further at risk. We need to: \u2022 Be aware of HIV, yet love people living with HIV; \u2022 Avoid becoming infected with the virus and avoid infecting others; \u2022 Avoid misconceptions surrounding means of transmission; \u2022 Support those who are vulnerable to HIV infection; \u2022 Avoid advocating the seclusion of those vulnerable, infected or affected by HIV. \u2022 Even churchgoers could be involved in behaviours that could put them at risk of contracting HIV such as unprotected sex with someone of unknown HIV status or injecting drugs using the same syringe or needle. \u2022 In fact, our motive to move only in concern for the protection of the \u201cnormal\u201d people, avoiding true care for people who are most vulnerable or those living with HIV is but another proof of our lack of love and zeal for the souls Christ died for. \u2022 The mission of the Church is to reach out with the love of God to EVERY PERSON. \u2022 The dangers posed by the HIV pandemic require us to reach out to vulnerable people. In fact, we should have moved much earlier. \u2022 Our aim is not merely to protect the healthy and righteous but to help the ailing and sinners. No condemnation 2 For in the same way you judge others, you will be judged, and with the measure you use, it will be measured to you. 3 \u201cWhy do you look at the speck of sawdust in your brother\u2019s eye and pay no attention to the plank in your own eye? 4 How can you say to your brother, \u2018Let me take the speck out of your eye,\u2019 when all the time there is a plank in your own eye? 5 You hypocrite, first take the plank out of your own eye, and then you will see clearly to remove the speck from your brother\u2019s eye. (Matthew 7:2-5) 23 for all have sinned and fall short of the glory of God, (Romans 3: 23) 10 For whoever keeps the whole law and yet stumbles at just one point is guilty of breaking all of it. (James 2: 10) \u2022 Supporting those most vulnerable to HIV should be based on love rather than condemnation. \u2022 As Mother Teresa says: if we are to judge and condemn others, we will have no time left to love them. \u2022 Love is to open doors for people to change, such as establishing recovery and support groups for drug users, and developing and promoting an accepting and caring environment for the marginalised. Protecting the lives of those in danger 3 The teachers of the law and the Pharisees brought in a woman caught in adultery. They made her stand before the group 4 and said to Jesus, \u201cTeacher, this woman was caught in the act of adultery. 5 In the Law Moses commanded us to stone such women. Now what do you say?\u201d as a trap, in order to have a basis for accusing him. But Jesus bent down and started to write on the ground with his finger. 7 When they kept on questioning him, he straightened up and said to them, \u201cIf any one of you is without sin, let him be the first to throw a stone at her.\u201d8 Again he stooped down and wrote on the ground. 9 At this, those who heard began to go away one at a time, the older ones first, until only Jesus was left, with the woman still standing there.10 Jesus straightened up and asked her, \u201cWoman, where are they? Has no one condemned you?\u201d 11 \u201cNo one, sir,\u201d she said. \u201cThen neither do I condemn you,\u201d Jesus declared. \u201cGo now and leave your life of sin.\u201d (John 8: 3-11) \u2022 Some people are infected through extra-marital sex; some through marital sex (because their husband or wives is infected); others are infected by other means. \u2022 Jesus did not condemn the woman who had sex outside marriage and challenged", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "ea0cc8de-3a8e-499a-aa5a-192b75541165": {"__data__": {"id_": "ea0cc8de-3a8e-499a-aa5a-192b75541165", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-guide-responding-hiv-christian-ministers-pastors-and-communities", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "A Pacific Guide on Responding to HIV for Christian Ministers, Pastors and Communities", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-guide-responding-hiv-christian-ministers-pastors-and-communities", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "680b7afd16172c840808380bc525e124a3e945591a285d5781fb3ed41d626d13"}}, "hash": "680b7afd16172c840808380bc525e124a3e945591a285d5781fb3ed41d626d13", "text": "the religious people who called for her punishment to stone her only if they themselves were without sin. \u2022 Jesus made it clear that we have no right to consider ourselves better than others; even if we do not fall into certain sins, we do fall into others. \u2022 Are we prone to condemn people living with HIV, assuming they were infected through extra-marital sex? If so, this Bible passage calls us to repent. \u2022 Do we condemn those who have sex outside marriage, reject them and seek to apply the Law of Moses on them? Do we seek to stone them or kill them, literally or emotionally? If so, those verses call us to repent. \u2022 The \u201cwoman was caught in the act\u201d; the law condemned the man as well but what happened to him? \u2022 In our society, do we tend to be more lenient with men who fall into sexual sins than with women? Do we tend to condemn women, holding them more accountable than men? \u2022 In what other areas are we being unfair to women in our society - not treating them equally - and giving men more rights than we do to women? \u2022 Let us pray for God to grant us justice and equality in all our dealings and, above all else, to be loving and humble that we may not condemn but rather love people \u2013 men and women - that our lives might be a source of blessings and salvation to them. \u2022 Protecting the lives of those rendered vulnerable by their behaviours or the behaviours of others, is likewise a holy mission for they are loved by the Lord. \u2022 How do we open the doors of change and repentance? \u2022 Calling upon people to undergo radical changes in their lifestyles does not contradict with alerting them to the dangers of risky behaviour and to the available means of prevention. \u2022 If it is unfeasible to provide alternative livelihood for commercial sex workers (prostitutes), or if they reject alternative livelihoods, it is still essential to make sure they have access to means of protection such as condoms as well as their clients, this could protect their lives until the right time comes for them to be able to change their lifestyle. Guideline for Christian Leaders Guideline for Christian Leaders 40 41 \u2022 This also applies to injecting drug users. \u2022 We must persistently call upon people to lead pure and holy lives. However, this call is not effective when it comes in hollow words and trumpet preaching; it only succeeds through perseverance in love, unconditional acceptance, refusal to condemn and understanding and listening to people who are marginalised because their behaviours are frowned upon by society. Change needs time, effort and spiritual and emotional support. Care and treatment for people living with HIV \u2022 Small groups of people living with HIV gathering to support one another may have significant and beneficial emotional, spiritual and even physical effects on their members. \u2022 The Lord commanded us to visit, care and pray for the ailing. Undertaking such visits and prayers is an essential mission for every Christian minister. \u2022 We need to encourage anyone who thinks he or she might have been exposed to HIV infection to undergo the necessary medical test (voluntarily) and to receive psychological counselling both before and after the test. \u2022 We need to assist people living with HIV however we can. This includes advocating for medication to be available to them and encouraging them to live a healthy and balanced life in all aspects: physically, emotionally and spiritually. A prayer to the Lord to send us out to minister 37 Then he said to his disciples, \u201cThe harvest is plentiful but the workers are few. (Matthew 9: 37-38) \u2022 We pray that the Lord would send labourers among us to work in His field; to bring salvation to souls before the fatal pandemic destroys them. \u2022 We pray that the Lord will fill us with the Spirit of prayer and supplication and that, through the Spirit, we might win many souls and save many bodies. Lord, send your Holy Spirit for your people to change into ministers working for your Amazing Glory. Lesson Seven A message to youth; be aware of HIV Themes: The Lord calls you to lead a fulfilling and fruitful life Avoid lusty desires; seek purity and self-control A message to those involved in risky behaviour A call for change A call to protect yourself The Lord loves and wishes to protect you and He wishes to save your soul HIV and", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "2a348d2a-233c-4cb7-9cd2-8aa5445ae42e": {"__data__": {"id_": "2a348d2a-233c-4cb7-9cd2-8aa5445ae42e", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-guide-responding-hiv-christian-ministers-pastors-and-communities", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher":