Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "A Pacific Guide on Responding to HIV for Christian Ministers, Pastors and Communities", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-guide-responding-hiv-christian-ministers-pastors-and-communities", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "9f6984eb50af2f5402eb7edf671019699f3a75fa76ee76f43ed2ba27955291a0"}}, "hash": "9f6984eb50af2f5402eb7edf671019699f3a75fa76ee76f43ed2ba27955291a0", "text": "in 2004-2005 found that around one fifth of students questioned reported that they had exchanged sex for money or goods in the previous year. When young people who had left school were included, the figure rose to more than one quarter. The exchange of sex for money or goods involved children as young as 11 years. Few young people used condoms consistently or at all. In Vanuatu, two fifths of youth out of school reported that they had exchanged sex for money or goods in the previous year. Again, few reported consistent condom use. Source: Buchanan-Aruwafu, H., 2007b. An Integrated picture: HIV Risk and Vulnerability in the Pacific: Research Gaps, Priorities and Approaches. Young women are affected by changing social attitudes and sexual practices, which have generally increased the extent of premarital and extramarital sex, even while reproductive health services remain largely restricted to married women, especially in more conservative rural communities. But young women also often fear that carrying or asking for condoms will brand them as promiscuous. As in many other parts of the world, many young people in the Pacific experience their first sexual encounter through force and coercion. Surveys in Samoa, Cook Islands and Kiribati found high levels of pressure and force involved in the first sexual experience of many young people. Young people can also be involved in higher risk practices such as drug use, transactional sex and male-to-male sex. Many young men (especially in all-male environments such as boarding schools or young men\u2019s houses) engage in same-sex behaviour (which does not necessarily include penetrative sex) but do not identify as being bisexual or homosexual. Relatively few young people report having sex with sex workers but the level of transactional sex is high. There are serious gaps in information on what influences these behaviours, why condom use remains low, or the specific contexts in which transactional sex and sexual violence occur. Clearly it is desirable that all countries should focus on carrying out systematic and repeated research studies of young people\u2019s behaviours, knowledge and the barriers to putting what they do know into practice. Source: Report of the Commission on AIDS in the Pacific 22 Flee the evil desires of youth, and pursue righteousness, faith, love and peace, along with those who call on the Lord out of a pure heart. (2 Timothy 2: 22) 3 For you died, and your life is now hidden with Christ in God. 4 When Christ, who is your life, appears, then you also will appear with him in glory. 5 Put to death, therefore, whatever belongs to your earthly nature: sexual immorality, impurity, lust, evil desires and greed, which is idolatry. (Colossians 3: 3-5) \u2022 Self-control starts in the heart. \u2022 A pure heart is one full of love. \u2022 Your love for others is not a desire to use their bodies for your lustful pleasure. \u2022 Strong love is utter purity. \u2022 The Bible calls upon us all, both women and men, to love with brotherly love. \u2022 We are called to treat people as humans - brothers and sisters - not tools to fulfil our lustful desires and instincts. \u2022 Pornography does not regard people as humans but as tools for lust. \u2022 Avoid things that stir lust in your life and encourage and cherish what enhances respect, love and fraternity among people. \u2022 Guard your physical eyes from lust provoking scenes and your mind\u2019s eyes from lustful imagining. \u2022 Your genuine relationship with God and loving ministry to others gives you the power to overcome lustful desires. \u2022 We are more than conquerors in Christ; He loved us and gave us His purity, joy, love and holiness. \u2022 Delight yourself in the Lord; rejoice in Him, be filled with His love \u2013 be enriched enough to stay away from the lustful desires of the world and the selfishness of the flesh. Guideline for Christian Leaders Guideline for Christian Leaders 46 47 A message to those involved in risky behaviour 18 \u201cThe Spirit of the Lord is on me, because he has anointed me to preach good news to the poor. He has sent me to proclaim freedom for the prisoners and recovery of sight for the blind, to release the oppressed, 19 to proclaim the year of the Lord\u2019s favor.\u201d (Luke 4: 18-19). 30 Even as he spoke, many put their faith in him. 31 To the Jews who had believed him, Jesus said, \u201cIf you hold to my teaching, you are really my disciples. 32 Then you will know the truth, and the truth will set you free.\u201d 33 They answered him,", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "93701e60-8e58-4961-8a3d-31009fdd068f": {"__data__": {"id_": "93701e60-8e58-4961-8a3d-31009fdd068f", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-guide-responding-hiv-christian-ministers-pastors-and-communities", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "A Pacific Guide on Responding to HIV for Christian Ministers, Pastors and Communities", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-guide-responding-hiv-christian-ministers-pastors-and-communities", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c6ebc0022591c4bc7c322144b8619d3410676e1e467bf021ba3ff8ff4b5993c5"}}, "hash": "c6ebc0022591c4bc7c322144b8619d3410676e1e467bf021ba3ff8ff4b5993c5", "text": "\u201cWe are Abraham\u2019s descendants and have never been slaves of anyone. How can you say that we shall be set free?\u201d 34 Jesus replied, \u201cI tell you the truth, everyone who sins is a slave to sin. 35 Now a slave has no permanent place in the family, but a son belongs to it forever. 36 So if the Son sets you free, you will be free indeed. (John 8: 30-36). 20 Here I am! I stand at the door and knock. If anyone hears my voice and opens the door, I will come in and eat with him, and he with me. (Revelation 3: 20) \u2022 No matter how strongly you believe that you cannot change the sexual behaviour or drug use you are involved in, there is hope. \u2022 You cannot change alone but Christ is able to set you free. \u2022 What you are unable to do, He is able to fulfill and accomplish. \u2022 When you ask Him for freedom, your eyes will be enlightened by His love, and His power will fill your heart. \u2022 You may be delivered in a minute, or you may start climbing a long hill towards recovery. \u2022 If you are determined to find deliverance, He will enable you to achieve it. \u2022 He is standing at the door; do not keep Him waiting. Open the door of your heart and allow Him to change your life today, then ask Him to do the same thing tomorrow and the day after and on every day of your life. \u2022 Radical change in your life requires regular attendance of rehabilitation and support programmes and groups. \u2022 The Lord called His disciples for change, and made sure that they were regularly in groups that encouraged them and where they could sense His presence and love. \u2022 The Lord calls you to join groups of people who battle for freedom and He promises you that you will find His presence and freedom within them. A call to protect yourself I have no problem with providing condoms under certain circumstances. My job as a pastoral worker is to help meet the needs of the people in my parish, not to judge them. (Sister Rose Bernard, Banz, Papua New Guinea. Sister Rose has been looking after and counseling HIV-positive people and their families since 1990.) \u2022 Whilst it is important that you change your behaviours, the decision is yours. Even if change is far away, the Lord still loves and cares for you. \u2022 Keep yourself and others safe from HIV. \u2022 Safe sex is a step forward towards responsible sex. \u2022 Use condoms while having sex with someone of unknown HIV status; it will protect your life and that of your partner from the risk of infection with HIV. \u2022 If you are injecting drugs, do not share contaminated syringes or needles. This will protect you from the risk of infection with HIV. \u2022 The Lord is patient; He loves and protects you from many dangers to which you might expose yourself or others through being involved in risky behaviour. \u2022 If you have extra-marital sex without using a condom, or if you share a contaminated syringe or needle, you should take a blood test and find out if you have become infected with HIV. \u2022 God willing, the test may relieve you from unnecessary worries. \u2022 If you are HIV-negative, take precautions to stay that way. \u2022 If you are HIV-positive, it is important that you find out your health condition as soon as possible in order to maximize your chances of improving your condition by medication, therapy and the right nutrition. \u2022 Safeguard your life on earth and your eternal life by self-control and faithfulness. \u2022 If you are delaying the change in your lifestyle, or if cannot refrained from risky behaviour, or if you are not willing to undergo this change, do not risk your health and possibly your life and those of others: use a condom while having sex and a clean syringe while injecting drugs. The Lord loves and wishes to protect you and He wishes to save your soul But now, this is what the LORD says-- he who created you, O Jacob, he who formed you, O Israel: \u201cFear not, for I have redeemed you; I have summoned you by name; you are mine. 2 When you pass through the waters, I will be with you; and when you pass through the rivers, they will not sweep over you. When you walk through the fire, you will not be burned; the flames will not set", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "d9a38224-cfb0-49f6-a292-738e0264a8ea": {"__data__": {"id_": "d9a38224-cfb0-49f6-a292-738e0264a8ea", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-guide-responding-hiv-christian-ministers-pastors-and-communities", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "A Pacific Guide on Responding to HIV for Christian Ministers, Pastors and Communities", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-guide-responding-hiv-christian-ministers-pastors-and-communities", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "621646b8e825568e0cf0809478cead49096cc993112c275b851a03a93770cdbd"}, "3": {"node_id": "103b54d2-7597-438d-a192-90d4a35da28b", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/pacific-guide-responding-hiv-christian-ministers-pastors-an