a \u2013 this briefing", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "61ac8197-f95e-40ba-a5b7-8e43ca65a7db": {"__data__": {"id_": "61ac8197-f95e-40ba-a5b7-8e43ca65a7db", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "A Preliminary Study of the Impact of HIV on Poverty and Food Security Among HIV-affected Households in Asia", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "590cee3988cd915dc3813c3a6844620c9edfd53f990188a8773ba32596bb6a80"}, "3": {"node_id": "b5e8eb0a-dfdb-45d5-a8ac-d0460ffad768", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "2e43e70622bf25c68bce17f310adcbc015af10953762c301ac82c1e92d703c52"}}, "hash": "16811251a890eea436a23ca19b42f557ea59d678a2066312f8e5025193b635b7", "text": "paper is the first of its kind in the region. In this context, this paper attempts to generate space for further discussions, research and actions on HIV-related food security risks, as part of UNDP\u2019s contributions to addressing the AIDS epidemic from human development perspectives. We wish to acknowledge the contribution of the HIV Team members who worked on this paper: Kazuyuki Uji and Tiruni Yasaratne and RCC\u2019s Knowledge Resources Committee members: Rohini Kohli, Nabeel Salie, Lionel Siriwardena, Maneka Weddikkara, and Chatrini Weeratunge for their valuable inputs. The valuable support provided by Charmalee Jayasinghe and Manisha Mishra is also greatly appreciated. Foreword Omar Noman Chief of Policies and Programmes UNDP Regional Centre in Colombo Caitlin Wiesen Regional HIV Practice Leader and Programme Coordinator for Asia and the Pacific III FAO . . . . . . Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations IFPRI. . . . . . International Food Policy Research Institute IMF . . . . . . International Monetary Fund NGO. . . . . . Nongovernmental Organization ODI . . . . . . Overseas Development Institute OVC . . . . . . Orphans and Vulnerable Children PLHIV . . . . . People Living with HIV UNDP . . . . . United Nations Development Program ACronyms And AbbreviAtions 1 Statement of the Problem HIV strikes people in the most pro- ductive age. AIDS is currently the leading cause of death among peo- ple between 15 and 44 years old in Asia1. While the aggregate econom- ic impact of HIV is often negligible in Asia, it can exert devastating ef- fects on households. The Commission of AIDS in Asia report2 estimates that every AIDS death could result in an income loss of $5,000 on average. The report also projects that an additional 6 million households in Asia will have been pushed below the poverty line by 2015 given the current level of HIV prevention, treatment and care & support activities. This could jeopardise the achievement of the MDGs. Recent food price inflation in Asia warrants a careful analysis of its im- pact on households affected by HIV. Since 2000, food prices have been rising in Asia and the Pacific and throughout the world, with par- ticularly sharp increases since 2007. Recent projections on how these in- creases affect the poor in develop- ing countries show that increases in the poverty headcount are likely to be severe, eliminating much of the progress in poverty reduction that has been made in recent years. For families affected by HIV, the situation is potentially even more precarious. HIV-affected house- holds are likely to have lost income due to the disease or discrimination in some cases, or because a family member who would otherwise be working is needed to provide care for someone living with HIV in the household. HIV-affected households also have direct costs for medical care that are fairly inflexible. Finally, since households living in poverty tend to spend a higher percentage of total expenditures on food, medi- cal expenses must often come out 1 Commission on AIDS in Asia (2008): Redefining AIDS in Asia: Crafting an effective response. Oxford University Press. 2 Ibid. Chapter One ExEcutivE Summary A Preliminary Study of the Impact of HIV on Poverty and Food Security Among HIV-affected Households in Asia 2 of the (already inadequate) house- hold food budget. There are several reasons why mal- nutrition is particularly risky for people living with HIV (PLHIV), in- cluding that deficiencies in micro- nutrients augment the disease\u2019s progression and that HIV infection also increases body\u2019s need for en- ergy. It is particularly important for those undergoing antiretroviral treatment (HIV treatment) to re- ceive sufficient nutrition. This paper investigates the potential impact of rising food prices in Asia on HIV-affected households in two ways. First, it presents a review of the research to date on how HIV affects the household economy. Second, it analyzes data from household studies in five countries to investi- gate specific ways that food price increases could affect households.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperato