IV-affected households with higher incomes spend more money on protein-rich foods like meat, eggs and dairy products and nutrient-rich foods like vegetables and fruits. Poor HIV-affected households are financially more vulnerable and less able to withstand external shocks. HIV-affected households have much higher amounts of dissavings and borrowing than non-HIV households. Debts can further weaken their ability to buy sufficient quantity and quality of food items particularly at the time of increasing food prices. The provision of food support targeting poor HIV-affected households could be highly beneficial and effective. In Cambodia, the food support program had a strong positive impact. The intervention households spent a much lower percentage of expenditures on food as well as on medical costs. Lower medical costs can be presumed to be the result of better nutrition and better health. There is the presence of potential HIV threats to the agricultural sector and therefore food security. The study in China found a reduced farm activity, reduced area under cultivation as well as non-diversity of crops among HIV-affected farm households compared with non-affected farm households. Among the most obvious research gaps in the Asian region is the lack of good quality longitudinal data on the impact of HIV on households and food security. No study has followed HIV-affected households over time to see how they react to changing economic conditions and changing HIV-related policies. This need is urgent as we have already entered uncertain economic times, and policy makers are still debating how to respond to the economic crises and to protect the most vulnerable through various safety nets. 3 By the mid-2000s, many well-de- signed studies have investigated the impact of HIV on the house- hold economy. However, only a few studies have included matched samples of households affected and not affected by HIV, so that di- rect comparisons may be made of the household economy. Five relevant studies were analysed to examine the potential impact of higher food prices on HIV-affected households in Asia. Three of the studies, from China (A total of 2,043 households were surveyed), India (8,292 households) and Thailand (600 households), include matched samples from HIV-affected and non-HIV- affected households. The Cambodian study (684 households) examined two types of HIV-affect- ed households (including people living with HIV [PLHIV] and with orphans (due to AIDS) and vulner- able children [OVC]) and compares households who were beneficiaries of an integrated food support and home-based care program with those of similar income and com- position who were not. Finally, the Vietnam study investigated expen- diture patterns of 125 households that included a PLHIV in four cities. While there are variations among the countries studied, the analysis indicates that rises in food prices will likely impact the quality as well as the quantity of diets for HIV- affected households. It was found that in some cases HIV-affected households had spent a lower proportion on food than those not affected, as well as a higher percentage on medical costs. HIV- affected households spent a lower percentage on food than their non- HIV counterparts, while wealthier house holds spent about the same percentage whether they were HIV- affected or not. This implies that poorer households were diverting money that they would otherwise spend on food to use for medical expenses. \u201cOther\u201d expenses show the sharp- est increase at higher wealth levels, especially for urban households. With regard to the quality of food, expenditures on grains did not vary much by income. As generally ex- pected, households with higher in- comes spent more money on pro- tein-rich foods like meat, eggs and dairy products and nutrient-rich foods like vegetables and fruits. The findings on coping strategies among HIV-affected households are similar to those found by other studies. The top answer on how they cover increased medical ex- penses, mentioned by one-third of respondents, was to borrow from friends and relatives. Nearly the same proportion said that they had used their savings for medical expenses and another one-quarter said that they liquidated assets. HIV households were found to have much higher amounts of dissav- ings and borrowing than non-HIV households, reflecting these strate- gies.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "9a9f22d6-db21-4505-9c91-1dbfd0cacd6a": {"__data__": {"id_": "9a9f22d6-db21-4505-9c91-1dbfd0cacd6a", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "A Preliminary Study of the Impact of HIV on Poverty and Food Security Among HIV-affected Households in Asia", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "4f4b033f1c778d10efed08d10ed630d325b62a7550bd144f2801982b819102fd"}, "2": {"node_id": "c14b50f2-caf6-43e2-90d1-ddb436dfe228", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "27b366ae997364c05