ia, the findings clearly show the positive impact of the food support program as the inter- vention households spent a much lower percentage of expenditures on food. Interestingly, they also paid a lower percentage on medical costs; since no additional medical services were provided as part of the program, this can be presumed to be a result of better health status due to improved food security. Comparing the control and inter- vention households, it is seen that the intervention households (re- ceiving the food support) generally spent the money they had saved on food and medical expenses on children\u2019s education and \u201cother\u201d expenses. The HIV-affected house- holds show similar differences in expenditure patterns between the control and intervention samples, although the difference in food expenditures is less sharp. Inter- vention households spent less on grains, as rice was provided to the households as part of the food support program. They also spent A Preliminary Study of the Impact of HIV on Poverty and Food Security Among HIV-affected Households in Asia 4 more money on protein-rich foods, indicating that the food support program had enhanced both the quality and quantity of food for these households. Additionally, the program enabled HIV-affected households to invest in children\u2019s education. The Vietnam study focused on HIV- affected households only. When asked the major sources of pay- ment for health expenses, only the poorest households reported that they had sold assets to pay for healthcare costs. The use of savings increased with household income while the use of borrowing de- creases. The study found that HIV- affected households had reduced consumption expenditures that they would otherwise make by be- tween 37% (for the poorest house- holds) and 42% (for the wealthiest households). With regard to pov- erty, they found that all households below the wealthiest quintile (in other words, 80% of households) would fall below the poverty line as a result of the income and expendi- ture effects of HIV. Future Studies Needed Among the most obvious research gaps in the Asian region is the lack of good quality longitudinal data on the impact of HIV on households. No study has followed households over time to see how they react to changing economic conditions. This need is urgent as we have al- ready entered uncertain economic times, and policy makers are still debating how to respond to global food needs and other aspects of the economic crises. At the same time, Asian govern- ments have responded in a variety of ways to meet the needs of PL- HIV and their households. It is im- portant to see the impact of these programs over time, including pro- grams addressing health-including antiretroviral treatment, care and support including psychosocial support, health insurance schemes, and other medical services-as well as food support and financial as- sistance programs should be exam- ined. More detail is also needed on the impact of antiretroviral treatment on households in Asia. The recently con- ducted studies in India and China also show evidence that the food situation is less severe for households with free antiretroviral drugs available, in com- parison to the high medical expen- ditures reported by Thai households in the 1999 study. The issue of the household economy, food security and risk behavior has also not been examined. As part of this research, attention should be paid to include the long-term impact of HIV as part of study designs. Most of the studies to-date have been cross-sectional, meaning that they provide a snapshot in time of house- holds with a PLHIV member at differ- ent stages of the disease. By analyz- ing how households react to different stages of illness and death and often volatile economic circumstances, pro- grams can be better designed to deal with varying needs. Finally, the topic of how agricultural and other liveli- hood systems interact with the HIV- affected household, particularly with regard to food production has not been sufficiently investigated in Asia. 5 Chapter Two introduction Recent food price inflation in Asia warrants a careful analysis of its im- pact on households affected by HIV. Thailand, for example, has witnessed a two-fold increase in the price of rice in the first quarter of 2008 [4]. The International Monetary Fund estimates that food prices have risen 65.7% globally from mid-2005 to August 2008 [32]. Price increases have been driven by several fac- tors, including the declining supply of rice and other cereals relative to consumption; fuel", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "359a9f9b-b19d-4b39-9a66-cf91111c693f": {"__data__": {"id_": "359a9f9b-b19d-4b39-9a66-cf91111c693f", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "A Preliminary Study of the Impact of HIV on Poverty and Food Security Among HIV-affected Households in Asia", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "fac43eb1ecba1d547bdf9ad671bd6cfff682e54b14c547c84dc07efd279edea2"}, "3": {"node_id": "c716d0ec-c2a5-497f-a666-5b4a110987be", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "335ea771e661f4cd77e62c59896700960a41bbe3f0adf963d275639015ce46d9"}}, "hash": "aacc40f6cc785dcbf32b21818f64833891bf7823d33e804d1af7ec13cccb5e32", "text": "scarcity; adverse weather; turmoil in financial mar- kets making commodities an attrac- tive investment; changes in dietary habits globally towards higher meat and dairy consumption; conversion of grain to biofuels; competing de- mands for land; and many others [4]. Recent projections on how these in- creases affect the poor in develop- ing countries show that increases in the poverty headcount are likely to be severe, eliminating much of the progress in poverty reduction that has been made in recent years. Moreover, the favorable effect of higher prices on rural food produc- ers is projected by several studies to be minimal [4, 5, 33, 62]. Given the impoverishing effects of HIV in Asia and the Pacific, current food price inflation could further exacerbate economic challenges for HIV-affected households [3, 35, 49]. In particular, a rapid food price increase could cause a greater number of vulnerable HIV-affected households to fall below the food poverty line. The reasons for this may be outlined as follows: HIV-affected households are ` likely to have lost income due to the disease. Most persons living with HIV (PLHIV) are adults in the working age groups who may lose time at work due to illness or be forced to stop working altogether. HIV-affected households may ` also lose income because a family member who would otherwise be working is needed to provide care for someone with HIV in the household. HIV-affected households have ` direct costs that are fairly inflexible. Medical costs normally have to be paid in cash and at the time A Preliminary Study of the Impact of HIV on Poverty and Food Security Among HIV-affected Households in Asia 6 of service. Transportation costs are also associated with seeking medical care and have been rising as well. ` Households living in poverty tend to spend a higher percentage of total expenditures on food. For HIV-affected households, medical expenses must thus of necessity come out of the (already inadequate) household food budget. ` For persons living with HIV, not getting an adequate nutrition supply is lethal. This is particularly true for those on antiretroviral treatment. This paper investigates the impact of rising food prices in Asia on HIV- affected households in two ways. First, it presents a review of the re- search to date on how HIV affects the household economy. Second, it ana- lyzes data from household studies in five countries to investigate specific ways that food price increases could affect households. The key objective of the paper is to assess the impact of HIV on food security and identify gaps in current research on this topic in Asia. Methodology Data from five country studies are analyzed to examine the potential impact of higher food prices on HIV- affected households. Three of the studies, from China, India and Thai- land, include matched samples from HIV-affected and non-HIV-affected households [34, 53]. This allows us to compare how having an HIV-positive member makes household expendi- ture patterns differ for households that are otherwise similar. The Cambodian study examines two types of HIV-affected households: those including one or more PLHIV and those including one or more orphans and vulnerable children (OVC). This study compares house- holds who were beneficiaries of an integrated food support and home- based care program with those of similar income and composition who live in an area that has not yet been included in the program [56]. Finally, the Vietnam study investi- gated expenditure patterns of 125 households that included a family member living with HIV in four cit- ies [59]. Further details on these five studies are given in the Appendix. Differences in household expendi- tures and income between HIV-affect- ed and non-HIV-affected households are tested for statistical significance using an independent samples t- test. The independent samples t-test, with the variance of the two samples not assumed to be equal, was used rather than the paired samples t-test because the sampling for the two groups was done independently; that is to say, households were not selected as matched pairs. For exam- ining differences within the sample of HIV-affected or non-HIV-affected households-for example, whether lower income households spend more on food-the F-test is used. Limitations of the Study Due to time and space constraints, the focus of this paper is fairly nar- row.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "c716d0ec-c2a5-497f-a666-5b4a110987be": {"__data__": {"id_": "c716d0ec-c2a5-497f-a666-5b4a110987be", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "A Preliminary Study of the Impact of HIV on Poverty and Food Security Among HIV-affected Households in Asia", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "fac43eb1ecba1d547bdf9ad671bd6cfff682e54b14c547c84dc07efd279edea2"}, "2": {"node_id": "359a9f9b-b19d-4b39-9a66-cf91111c693f", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "aacc40f6cc785dcbf32b21818f64833891bf7823d33e804d1af7ec13cccb5e32"}}, "hash": "335ea771e661f4cd77e62c59896700960a41bbe3f0adf963d275639015ce46d9", "text": "It is limited to the situation of households that currently include an HIV-positive family member, and does not present findings on the impact of the death of a family member from AIDS. It also focuses narrowly on economic effects with little attention to how the issue of stigma and discrimination affects HIV households. Finally, while sever- al studies have", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "6fb517fd-40c7-469c-ad2b-28d3b00bf177": {"__data__": {"id_": "6fb517fd-40c7-469c-ad2b-28d3b00bf177", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "A Preliminary Study of the Impact of HIV on Poverty and Food Security Among HIV-affected Households in Asia", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ee1f9279f25bee68683de5a90702c2a33d748e95b78d698d5c9cabc6f3c435bb"}, "3": {"node_id": "ea4b659f-0d4b-4547-a0bf-8293314b5792", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "940424957b3be8a2bfd5ac0926cca4c31b28dd64a954ecdaff7ca0b068f47290"}}, "hash": "71a565fa13f82d7274c4aafbca16a4148f74834de71974efc480a5da7ec31a23", "text": "established the link between HIV, food insecurity, migra- tion and risk behavior, particularly in Africa, this paper only examines economic consequences for static households that are currently HIV- affected without regard to migra- tion in and out of these households [9, 16, 20, 46, 61]. While fuel prices have also been ris- ing steeply in recent years, it was not possible to examine fuel expendi- tures with these data as not enough information was collected by the studies. Transportation costs are examined where possible, but fuel costs are not separated from other transportation costs. Also, transpor- tation costs related to medical treat- ment are included with medical costs in some of the studies. While the five studies used for data analysis all contain rich data for this topic, they do not measure all fac- tors in the same way; these differ- ences are noted when known. 7 Chapter Three Background Price Increases and the Impact on Poverty The steep rise in food prices world- wide in the past three years has been called \u201cthe silent tsunami\u201d in terms of its effect on world hunger [23]. The UN World Food Program estimates that it needs an addi- tional $700 million dollars to keep up current levels of food aid [22, 51] The causes of these increases, which have affected non-food com- modities as well, are complex and interrelated, involving increased demand, decreased supply and the impact of government policies. Rapidly growing emerging econ- omies-most notably China, India and oil-rich nations in the Middle East-have created an increased demand for food in general, but also for higher protein foods such as meat and dairy products, which require greater amounts of grain to produce. The demand for biofuels has also diverted grain commodi- ties away from the food market. In China, the increase in food prices is mainly driven by increases in meat prices, particularly pork, and in veg- etable oil prices rather than grain prices. At the same time several factors have driven decreases in the sup- ply of food, including urbanization, industrialization, increased land costs, and long-term underinvest- ment in agriculture by develop- ing countries. These long-term structural changes in the supply of food mean that the market is not responsive to recent increases in demand in the short run; in other words, there is a time lag before price increases stimulate increased food production. At the same time, many countries have instituted cri- sis policies, such as restricting ex- ports of food, that increase price in- stability globally. Another factor is that increased trading on commod- ity markets, in the wake of financial failures in other sectors such as banking and insurance, has driven food prices upward [4, 18, 24, 27, 31, 33, 51, 56]. A Preliminary Study of the Impact of HIV on Poverty and Food Security Among HIV-affected Households in Asia 8 Will Higher Food Prices Alleviate Rural Poverty? Some have expressed the hope that food price increases would be passed along to rural produc- ers, and that the overall impact of these increases would be to reduce poverty in rural areas of developing countries. Since urban households tend to have higher incomes than rural households, and net consum- ers of food\u2014who earn enough to buy food in the cash economy\u2014 have higher incomes than net producers, it would follow that an increased flow of cash would make its way to rural households if prices go up [2, 50, 51, 56]. Others have argued that these ben- efits are not likely to materialize. One reason is that poor families consume much of their own food production, so that there is no net gain in income if prices go up. An- other is that urban constituents tend to hold more political clout, and many governments have insti- tuted such policies as export bans, trade restrictions and price con- trols to alleviate anger (and riots in some locations) over food price increases. Prices of agricultural inputs such as fuel and fertilizer have also sharply increased, as have transport costs, reducing potentially increased profits for producers. The IMF has called for countries to increase ag- ricultural production to take advan- tage of the benefits of higher com- modity prices, but it is unclear how soon such increased production could benefit rural producers.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "ea4b659f-0d4b-4547-a0bf-8293314b5792": {"__data__": {"id_": "ea4b659f-0d4b-4547-a0bf-8293314b5792", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "A Preliminary Study of the Impact of HIV on Poverty and Food Security Among HIV-affected Households in Asia", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ee1f9279f25bee68683de5a90702c2a33d748e95b78d698d5c9cabc6f3c435bb"}, "2": {"node_id": "6fb517fd-40c7-469c-ad2b-28d3b00bf177", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "71a565fa13f82d7274c4aafbca16a4148f74834de71974efc480a5da7ec31a23"}}, "hash": "940424957b3be8a2bfd5ac0926cca4c31b28dd64a954ecdaff7ca0b068f47290", "text": "Finally, the poorest of the poor in rural areas are the landless; while demand and wage rates for daily labor may go up in response to higher profits, in the short run the rural poor are likely to suffer more than they benefit from higher food prices. Some experts have argued that careful analysis must be made", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "ff481033-d043-41ee-9a6c-612debd1b0b2": {"__data__": {"id_": "ff481033-d043-41ee-9a6c-612debd1b0b2", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "A Preliminary Study of the Impact of HIV on Poverty and Food Security Among HIV-affected Households in Asia", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "8e1febdb9209384c277abf56bf05d49e240cfb8ea2deb2ec0735d8e2f6760407"}, "3": {"node_id": "dae2d90e-eeb1-424b-9cab-ae74344bde07", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "acf9510ce1c13d8cfbea1ac18cb115d4372eea57be1b535040731c8e3723ff11"}}, "hash": "4f30744792bf65f032630d61323cffb19b164c0ee8b80e4b5db7624e04de04c6", "text": "for individual countries to design trade policies that allow the ben- efits of higher prices to reach the poor, while in the short term many poor households will need emer- gency food aid [5, 8, 18, 22, 31, 45]. How Higher Food Prices may Impact Poverty Several recent studies have attempt- ed to estimate the impact of higher food prices on poverty. In China, ru- ral real incomes grew 9.5% due to price increases, in spite of input costs rising by 20%. The impact of higher prices on the urban poor however led the Chinese government to in- crease food subsidies [56]. A recent study by the World Bank uses household consumption and production data from nine coun- tries to estimate the impact of higher food prices on both food consumption and wages [33]. It concludes that the overall impact of higher food prices will be to increase poverty headcounts by 4.5%\u2014a loss of seven years of pov- erty reduction\u2014since most poor households are net consumers of food. While some rural producers may benefit, the large numbers of urban households already living close to the poverty line means that these benefits are far outweighed by increasing numbers of house- holds falling into poverty. Another World Bank study argues that the interrelationships between net food buyers and net food sell- ers are complex and that estimates of the impact of higher prices can- not be made without analyzing these [2]. A few studies have attempted to measure the impact on the pov- erty rate using national household surveys. An ADB study also found that food price increases would greatly increase the number of poor households in the Philippines and Pakistan [4]. At the same time a study using Indian household data showed that an increase in the price of rice would have a net benefit to poor households [52]. This study simulated changes in wages for ru- ral workers as well as producers. Another study using household expenditure and production data was used to estimate the impact of recent price increases on both con- sumption and income from produc- tion. The study found that increases in income from production were far outweighed by the negative impact of increased prices on con- sumption; the result was that an additional 2.8% of the population would fall under the poverty line after the 2006-2007 price increases and an additional 8.5% based on 2006-2008 price increases [62]. To summarize, recent analysis of how higher food prices will affect 9 poverty have come to varied con- clusions. The debate on the conse- quences of higher prices and how to best design policies to address these issues is complicated by re- cent economic changes globally, which need to be taken into ac- count in any future research and analysis. Poverty, Food Security and HIV Several have suggested that \u201ccop- ing strategies\u201d is an incorrect way to describe how HIV-affected house- holds manage to pay their extra expenses, and that \u201csurvival strate- gies\u201d would be more accurate [42, 54]. When such households already live at the margins, increased medi- cal expenses must either come from income that would be spent on other necessities, from savings, from liquidating assets or by going into debt. In Africa, the link between food se- curity risks and HIV infection is well established; as will be outlined in more detail below, household-level decreases in income, declines in food production and increased de- pendency are the causes of this [63]. In a comprehensive review of previ- ous studies published in 2005, the International Food Policy Research Institute (IFPRI) delineates 150 stud- ies providing evidence on the link between HIV and household size and composition, agriculture, food crises, and human capital; as well as of the impact of food and nutrition insecurity on the spread of HIV; nu- trition, HIV transmission and disease progression links; and antiretroviral therapy and nutrition [26]. In Asia and the Pacific however, few detailed studies have been con- ducted to establish this link [25, 37]. Only two of the studies referenced in the IFPRI review article are from Asia [26]. ADB (2006) completed a study estimating the effects of HIV on pov- erty for Papua New Guinea and the Fiji Islands using household expen- diture data.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "dae2d90e-eeb1-424b-9cab-ae74344bde07": {"__data__": {"id_": "dae2d90e-eeb1-424b-9cab-ae74344bde07", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "A Preliminary Study of the Impact of HIV on Poverty and Food Security Among HIV-affected Households in Asia", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash