t Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "9da952c762a867d561fb8c57a29e624ff707879bd4fe609c4b2064101a56a398"}, "3": {"node_id": "2b2407ae-cfa0-498e-bf7a-1f2383d1090a", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "4d85ad7b1eee0aa7ff5370610c0f58fda14c4be3e1f1ad5ca8cb809ae03d4bd9"}}, "hash": "0f710d54017983bc0dc4f14997301f271032c5cbb72a17c956e3f66b7d49e43e", "text": "HIV infection, suffer from weakened immune systems. When someone is infected with HIV, deficiencies in micronutrients have been found to augment the disease\u2019s progression. HIV infection also increases the need for energy and makes food more difficult to absorb, leading to the wasting ef- fects that are commonly seen in PLHIV. While antiretroviral treat- ment improves nutritional status, the side effects of antiretroviral therapy including nausea and vom- iting require that those under treat- ment continue to supplement their food intake. A recent study demon- strated that food supplementation for those undergoing antiretroviral treatment significantly improved adherence to medication [15, 60], which is indispensable to effective HIV treatment and the prevention of developing drug resistance. Previous Studies on the HIV-affected Household Economy Overview of Study Designs By the mid-2000s, many well-de- signed studies have investigated the impact of HIV on the house- hold economy. In a review article published in 2003, Booysen and Arntz outlined the four sampling approaches that have been taken to identify HIV-affected households for these studies [13]. Two methods are commonly used to recruit PLHIV: (1) through a clin- ic- or hospital-based program that provides treatment and/or other services [14, 21] or (2) through community based organizations or NGOs who work with PLHIV. A third method is to take a general popu- lation sample and then identify households where there is a recent death or chronic illness of a house- hold member. Some of these studies identify PLHIV through testing, but others never definitely confirm the HIV status of the household mem- ber. The fourth sampling method identified is to use some combina- tion of the first three methods. Booysen and Arntz also point out that some studies only interview the individual PLHIV without includ- ing other household members who may be more knowledgeable about the household economy, since the PLHIV may not have disclosed their A Preliminary Study of the Impact of HIV on Poverty and Food Security Among HIV-affected Households in Asia 10 status to family members. They also outline the inherent bias involved in using these sampling methods, since certain groups are less likely to give consent to be part of a study. These underrepresented groups include more affluent individuals, those with higher educational at- tainment and older men. Other factors affecting the repre- sentativeness of study findings in- clude that many do not include a matched \u201ccontrol group\u201d of house- holds that are not HIV affected for comparison, and that the sample size for these studies is usually small. Finally, formal sampling methods such as stratified random sampling are rarely used for these studies. Most studies examining the house- hold economy as affected by HIV use a structured questionnaire to collect a cross-sectional sample, but other methods have been used as well. Cohort or longitudinal studies are less common and more difficult to conduct, but provide valuable information on how the household economy changes as the illness progresses or the person dies. One study followed a sample of HIV- and non-HIV affected households for eighteen months and exam- ined how household expenditures change with morbidity and mortal- ity [6, 7, 10, 11, 12]. Several other recent studies have identified ART clients at treatment centers and fol- lowed them to see how work status, illness patterns, household expen- ditures and income change as the treatment progresses [29, 57]. A few studies have used qualita- tive methods such as in-depth in- terviews and focus group discus- sions to examine the social and economic impact of HIV on the family and household economy [44]. Some have used existing sec- ondary data to estimate the impact on the household, without includ- ing direct data on households with a PLHIV member. An example is Martin and Logan (2005) who used Demographic and Health Survey (DHS) and living standards surveys to estimate HIV-related income and expenditure effects [39]. Only a few studies have included matched samples of households affected and not affected by HIV, so that direct comparisons may be made of the household economy. One example from Thailand, which is examined in depth in the analysis section, studied HIV and non-HIV households in Phayao province [34, 35, 36, 49].", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "2b2407ae-cfa0-498e-bf7a-1f2383d1090a": {"__data__": {"id_": "2b2407ae-cfa0-498e-bf7a-1f2383d1090a", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "A Preliminary Study of the Impact of HIV on Poverty and Food Security Among HIV-affected Households in Asia", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "9da952c762a867d561fb8c57a29e624ff707879bd4fe609c4b2064101a56a398"}, "2": {"node_id": "e415b683-2475-49b5-9231-8f7e6aab3b14", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "0f710d54017983bc0dc4f14997301f271032c5cbb72a17c956e3f66b7d49e43e"}}, "hash": "4d85ad7b1eee0aa7ff5370610c0f58fda14c4be3e1f1ad5ca8cb809ae03d4bd9", "text": "The study found that the economic costs of HIV to house- holds are severe and fall hardest on the poor, who have a fewer coping strategies to fall back on. Further- more, the economic impact of an AIDS-related death was more severe than a death from another cause, and agricultural households and those with lower educational attain- ment were particularly hard hit. Booysen and Arntz also catalogued the geographic setting of studies on the socioeconomic impact", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "4eca26ef-86bd-435a-ae5c-0edf89cacb1e": {"__data__": {"id_": "4eca26ef-86bd-435a-ae5c-0edf89cacb1e", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "A Preliminary Study of the Impact of HIV on Poverty and Food Security Among HIV-affected Households in Asia", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "5be9078f8ab8379c41fe9b96e5888d514b91ae57989a1c94e531f13838426850"}, "3": {"node_id": "ae584f7e-ec6a-4d80-ab8b-f19c5aa33d5e", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "d4bc5b36c7307ef564b0e6e4e5f94c8c6502802fbe8fe6998c908320c9ced914"}}, "hash": "924ded2a471d3d0a89b39dafae2e3c9bc4269b22ba0e8f514d3fd1f7199ac8e3", "text": "of HIV/ AIDS published before 2003. They found that about 45% of the stud- ies were conducted in Africa, with about one-third in East Africa, and a heavy concentration in Uganda and Tanzania. Asia was represented by two studies in India, three in Thailand and one each in the Phil- ippines and Sri Lanka. While about half of the studies were set in urban areas and half in rural areas, those studies that identified respondents in a clinic or hospital in an urban setting may actually include many rural respondents. Two-thirds of the studies focused on morbidity rather than mortality. Finally, very few included quality of life scales or other psychosocial measures as part of their impact studies, as most focused on economic and health is- sues [13]. Key Findings from Household Studies Studies of the impact of HIV on the household have clustered around four key themes: the impact of the disease on the household economy and livelihoods; coping strategies that families use to deal with added medical expenses and loss of in- come; implications of the changes in the household economy for pov- erty and food security; and changes in the social structure, particularly of the family. By this point in the epidemic, a number of carefully done studies have reached similar conclusions about the implications of HIV for the household economy. House- holds affected by HIV are faced with extra medical costs that vary by country, but are nearly always much higher than those faced by 11 a non-HIV affected household. Fu- neral costs in the event of a death can also require substantial sums of money in some settings as well. Households lose income when PL- HIV members become less produc- tive with their illness and/or are forced to stop working altogether. Some also lose their jobs due to dis- crimination. Caregivers often give substantial time to caring for PLHIV and lose income through being less productive or having to give up their job as well. [1, 19, 47, 55, 59]. Naidu and Harris (2005) in a review of 32 studies published from 1995- 2005 classify costs to households as direct costs (expenditures on treat- ment and associated costs such as funerals and transportation) and indirect costs (loss of earnings of the PLHIV and caregiver(s) through reduced productivity) [42]. Indirect costs have consistently been found to be higher than direct costs, when calculated over the lifetime of the individual without illness [49]. Di- rect estimates of the impact of HIV on household income over a period of time (such as the year before the survey) are also commonly calcu- lated. Many of the studies focus on cop- ing strategies\u2014perhaps more accu- rately termed survival strategies\u2014 of HIV affected households. These strategies are examined both by asking household members what they do to cover increased medical and other costs and by collecting detailed information about expen- ditures, earned income, and other ways of obtaining funds including borrowing, selling assets, etc. The most common first response for households to cover extra costs is to use savings [21]. Many also rely on borrowing from friends and rel- atives, with borrowing from finan- cial institutions or moneylenders a less favored strategy. Selling assets including land and other means of production, is also a frequent strategy [14, 28]. Indebtedness is thus common among HIV affected households [21, 44]. Mutangadura (1999) delineates a framework for examining coping strategies for rural households by categorizing them into strategies aimed at improving food security, strategies aimed at raising or sup- plementing income, and strategies aimed as alleviating the loss of labor [41]. Some studies have gathered evidence to prioritize these strate- gies as the disease progresses, and as the household has fewer resourc- es to call on as savings are depleted and lending sources dry up. Two studies that demonstrate these survival strategies are highlighted here. Mikael (2004) uses a sustain- able livelihoods framework to out- line how HIV is a shock to the rural livelihood [40]. The households he studied borrowed from relatives and liquidated assets, such as live- stock, to cover medical costs. They also used such strategies as reduc- ing farm size by leasing land and selling land, due to the loss of labor caused by the illness itself and the need for care.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "ae584f7e-ec6a-4d80-ab8b-f19c5aa33d5e": {"__data__": {"id_": "ae584f7e-ec6a-4d80-ab8b-f19c5aa33d5e", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "A Preliminary Study of the Impact of HIV on Poverty and Food Security Among HIV-affected Households in Asia", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "5be9078f8ab8379c41fe9b96e5888d514b91ae57989a1c94e531f13838426850"}, "2": {"node_id": "4eca26ef-86bd-435a-ae5c-0edf89cacb1e", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "924ded2a471d3d0a89b39dafae2e3c9bc4269b22ba0e8f514d3fd1f7199ac8e3"}}, "hash": "d4bc5b36c7307ef564b0e6e4e5f94c8c6502802fbe8fe6998c908320c9ced914", "text": "In many cases the household is re- structured as children are sent to live elsewhere, family members are brought in to provide care, and household members migrate to earn cash remittances. These strat- egies combine to erode food secu- rity as the household livelihood be- comes less productive and through labor shortages less reliant on agri-", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "fed9678c-973b-43f4-bf6d-d5defe08d053": {"__data__": {"id_": "fed9678c-973b-43f4-bf6d-d5defe08d053", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "A Preliminary Study of the Impact of HIV on Poverty and Food Security Among HIV-affected Households in Asia", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "673b2684f9d76043320c683aa39a77393033fa3285b6476dec4a907952d98031"}, "3": {"node_id": "5270860f-3726-4b8e-a5de-c65f6305d0ad", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "71ccaf8f71e3608593cd59f95b4128f34bccfb28bdf06cc8454023b43726b967"}}, "hash": "6e22a31b09d20b0df047f5992653f0d41bad36c45e52441256beeeaf90e7b420", "text": "culture. Hilhorst et al. (2006) also delineate these factors, providing evidence that HIV has both time costs and pro- ductivity costs for PLHIV and caregiv- ers [27]. Besides the direct loss of job and income, the ability to run the A Preliminary Study of the Impact of HIV on Poverty and Food Security Among HIV-affected Households in Asia 12 farm is lost through reducing farm investments and liquidating means of production. The reduction in farm productivity, most importantly, leads to the erosion of food security for the household. Bukusuba et al. (2007) outline how some urban fam- ilies who practice small-scale farm- ing improve their food security and dietary diversity [14]. The impact of HIV on poverty has also been an important focus of household-level studies. Duraisamy et al. (2006) outlined how the bur- den of HIV care costs falls dispro- portionately on poorer households; since they lack savings and assets to liquidate, medical costs tend to come out of money that would be otherwise spent on food and other basic necessities [21]. Buku- suba et al. (2007) documented how households reduce food expenses by missing meals and by reducing dietary diversity [14]. Martin and Logan (2005) using household data from the Demographic and Health Survey (DHS) and Living Standards Survey (LSS) found that while in- come quintiles 2 through 5 expe- rienced decline in income by 15- 20%, the poorest quintile declined as much as 40%. They concluded that poverty reduction in the na- tion would slow as much as 25% from the impact of HIV [39]. Bachmann and Booysen\u2019s (2003) longitudinal study traces morbid- ity and mortality with expenditures and income. While expenditures were found to be a more sensitive indicator than income, they found that real expenditures decreased over time with morbidity [6]. Sev- eral studies have documented how children are often forced to drop out of school because the fam- ily cannot afford educational ex- penses and/or because their labor is needed at home\u2014eroding the longer-term financial prospects of poor families [39, 44, 55] Rules of inheritance and mourning practic- es also increase the vulnerability of the poor in many settings [28]. Recently several longitudinal stud- ies have outlined how antiretrovi- ral treatment, besides improving the health status of PLHIV, benefits the status of the whole household. A study from the state of Tamil Nadu, India systematically followed a large cohort of PLHIV receiving ART. It included information on quality of life, psychosocial sta- tus and socioeconomic status for both PLHIV and their families. The study found that as antiretroviral therapy clients gradually returned to the workforce and their health improved, the household reduced expenditures and borrowing. Con- sumption of food increased, which results in better health for all family members [29, 57]. Many studies have examined the impact of HIV on the family and on household structure. The main impact of the disease is to raise the dependency ratio within house- holds. When children are orphaned by AIDS, it is often the grandpar- ents who step in to care for them. Even with surviving but ill family members, older people find that they need to work beyond the age when they otherwise would have [44, 55]. Single parent households are also common through death or deser- tion of the spouse. Child headed households are often created with an older child dropping out of school and working, often in in- formal low paying jobs, to raise siblings. While traditional commu- nity support systems exist, Mikael points out that these systems are usually short-term and not suited to chronic illnesses like those re- lated to HIV [28, 40, 55]. 13 Chapter Four rESultS Expenditures of HIV- affected Households We first examine findings from the China, India and Thai studies as these have a similar design. Fig- ures 1.1-1.33 show the percentage of expenditures that HIV- and non- HIV-affected households spent on food, medical expenses and other household expenditures. In India (Fig.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "5270860f-3726-4b8e-a5de-c65f6305d0ad": {"__data__": {"id_": "5270860f-3726-4b8e-a5de-c65f6305d0ad", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "A Preliminary Study of the Impact of HIV on Poverty and Food Security Among HIV-affected Households in 