or the China data. A Preliminary Study of the Impact of HIV on Poverty and Food Security Among HIV-affected Households in Asia 14 6 While the Thai study was designed to examine differences between two districts with different levels of services, these differences are not examined for this draft due to time constraints. 7 Dr. Jianhua Yuan, personal communication. In Thailand (Fig. 1.3) HIV households spent a much higher percentage on medical expenses (t=31.4, p<.00), a much lower percentage on food (t=-10.3, p<.00) and lower percent- ages on transportation and other expenses (t=-5.4, p<.00).6 It should be remembered that health programs that serve PLHIV differ greatly in these countries and have also changed over time. At the time of the surveys, PLHIV in China receive antiretroviral treatment free of charge and some PLHIV in the In- dia study states do as well [53]. The China survey found that many of the respondents are currently re- ceiving antiretroviral treatment. 7 This reduces medical expenditures relative to those in other countries, but may increase travel costs. It could also lead to higher food ex- penditures as good nutrition is vi- tal to maintaining health for PLHIV under treatment and as mentioned above food helps to alleviate anti- retroviral drug side effects. This may explain the fact that HIV households spend about the same percentage on food as non-HIV households in China, even though they have high- er medical expenses. The Thai data was collected in 1999, before ART was available and at a time where there were fewer pro- grams available for PLHIV. Though health care services are relatively low-cost in Thailand, the cost of drugs can be quite high, as reflected in the high medical costs for HIV af- fected households in Thailand [34]. Figure 1.2 Percent of household expenditures by type of expenditure, HIV and non-HIV households, China Figure 1.3 Percent of monthly household expenditures by type of expenditure, HIV and non-HIV households, thailand Figure 2.1 Percent of monthly household expenditures on food by income quintile, HIV and non-HIV households, India Figure 1.1 Percent of monthly household expenditures by type of expenditure, HIV and non-HIV households, India 15 Figures 2.1-2.3 show how the per- centage spent on food differs for HIV-affected and non-affected households by income quintiles. In India the pattern is clear (Fig. 2.1): poorer HIV-affected households spend a lower percentage on food than their non-HIV counter-parts (F=87.1, p<.00), while wealthier households spend about the same percentage whether they are HIV- affected or not (F=0.5, p=.49). This implies that poorer households are diverting money that they would otherwise spend on food to use for medical expenses. In China (Fig 2.2) the pattern is a bit different as middle income and wealthier households that are HIV- affected spend a higher percentage on food than those who are not af- fected. This is likely because these households are attempting to en- sure better nourishment for PLHIV in the household, many of whom are receiving antiretroviral treat- ment. In Thailand (Fig. 2.3), there is a more dramatic difference in the percent- age spent on food between the HIV and non-HIV households, likely due to the high percentage spent on medical care seen above. The already low percentage of expendi- ture does not decline much by in- come quintile for HIV households in Thailand (F=4.3, p<.00), though the typical pattern is seen for non-HIV households (F=4.6, p<.00).", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "39222d7a-854d-460c-b652-ef8074ce1454": {"__data__": {"id_": "39222d7a-854d-460c-b652-ef8074ce1454", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "Unit