ong HIV-affected Households in Asia 16 durable goods and celebrations, as well as non-food non-transport re- lated daily expenditures that were reported on a monthly basis. In China (Figure 3.2) HIV-affected households spend more over- all than non-HIV households; al- though they spend about the same on food, they have higher medical and other expenses. As seen above the Thai households spent less on food per capita (Fig- ure 3.3) (t=-1.96, p=.05) but much more on medical expenses (t=14.2, p<.00), so that their overall per cap- ita expenses are higher. Figures 4a.1 and 4b.1 show monthly per capita expenditures by income quintile for rural and urban areas in India for the HIV-affected house- holds. The amount spent on medi- cal expenses goes up with income (rural F=6.7, urban F=16.0, p<.00) as do food expenditures (rural F=221.2, urban F=260.6, p<.00). \u201cOther\u201d expenses show the sharp- est increase at higher wealth lev- els, especially for urban house- holds (rural F=72.0, urban F=125.9, p<.00). Rural and urban households do not differ much in expenditure patterns by quintile except in the highest income quintile, where ur- ban households have much higher expenditures. As seen in Figure 4.2, the expendi- ture patterns by income are some- what different in China. Food ex- penditures increase steadily with income, while medical expenditures are fairly constant\u2014except for the middle income group, which has the lowest medical expenses. Since the rural medical insurance scheme in China is the same for all income groups, it is difficult to explain this finding.8 \u201cOther\u201d expenses also do not have a consistent pattern by income in the China sample, though the over- all trend is increasing by income. Interestingly, a similar pattern is seen in Thailand (Figure 4.3) with the middle income group having the lowest expenditures. In general, food expenditures increase with in- come (F=3.1, p=.01) as do medical expenditures (F=7.6, p<.00). Finally, Figures 5.1 and 5.2 shows differences in the type of foods purchased by income level for HIV- affected households in India and China. The patterns are very similar in the two countries. Expenditures on grains do not vary much by in- come. Households with higher in- comes spend more money on pro- tein-rich foods like meat, eggs and dairy products (F=189.6, p<.00) and nutrient-rich foods like vegetables and fruits (F=215.9, p<.00). This implies that rises in food prices will impact the quality as well as the quantity of diets for HIV-affected households.9 The Chinese study also reveals the impact of HIV on HIV-affected farm Figure 3.3 Per capita monthly household expenditures by type of expenditure, HIV and non-HIV households, thailand 8 Dr. Jianhua Yuan, personal communication. 9 Breakdowns in food expenditures by type of food were not included in the Thai study. Figure 4a.1 Per capita monthly household expenditures by type of expenditure by income quintile, rural HIV households, India 17 households. The study found the reduced farm activity, reduced area under cultivation as well as non-di- versity of crops among HIV-affected farm households as compared with corresponding non-affected farm households. For example, nearly 10% of the land owned by HIV-af- fected farm households was idle. In contrast, corresponding non- affected farm households needed more land (therefore leased) to meet their cultivation demands. These findings indicate a potential threat of HIV to the agricultural in- dustry and thus food security, as witnessed in some parts of Africa.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "403c06d5-195a-4e51-b4b1-64e590094e3b": {"__data__": {"id_": "403c06d5-195a-4e51-b4b1-64e590094e3b", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-