 that these households were not asked about liquidating assets. In urban areas, HIV households had higher income levels and added another 33% of per capita income through borrowing, dissavings and liquidating assets.12 Analysis of Program Impact in Cambodia As mentioned above, the Cambodia study was designed to measure the impact of integrating food support to households with a PLHIV or OVC with an existing Home-Based Care program. A sample of PLHIV and OVC households who had received the food support for three years (the intervention sample) was matched with a sample of households who had been identified for inclusion in the program but had not yet re- ceived support (the control sample). This section presents findings on household expenditures for these samples, allowing an examination of the impact of the food support program on the household econ- omy. All of the samples are HIV- affected however, so that no com- parison is possible with non-HIV affected households from the same communities. 10 Information on coping strategies was included in the Thai study but not provided for this draft. 11 Non-HIV-affected households were not asked about liquidating assets. 12 Information on borrowing, saving, and liquidating assets was included in the Thai and China studies but not available for this draft. table 1.2 Coping mechanisms for additional expenditures and loss of income, China Percent (%) Borrow from friends and relatives 60.7 Use past savings 25.5 Medical insurance 14.5 Liquidation of assets/durable goods/ livestock 10.9 Wife had to take up job in order to support the family 9.1 Borrow from moneylender and other financial institutions 9.0 Had to take up additional job 8.5 Children had to take up job 8.0 NGO support 4.6 Usury 2.0 (N = 1027) Multiple responses possible 19 Figure 4.3 Per capita monthly household expenditures by type of expenditure by income quintile, HIV households, thailand Figure 5.1 Per capita monthly household expenditures on food by type of foo