se households; however, the difference is not statis- tically significant (t=-1.1, p<.28). 13 \u201cCelebrations/social events\u201d was also a large category of expenditure, especially for wealthier households; this category was omitted from the analysis of household expenditures as it was so large as to make it difficult to examine differences in food consumption. Agricultural inputs were also excluded as they are generally not included in household consumption studies. 14 Expenditure rather than income quintiles are used because the survey did not collect information on income. A Preliminary Study of the Impact of HIV on Poverty and Food Security Among HIV-affected Households in Asia 20 The Cambodia study did not ask directly about coping strategies as the other surveys did, but did ask about loans and assets sold in the past year. Table 3.4 shows that the percentage who said they took a loan is relatively small, and does not differ for the control and interven- tion areas. When asked the purpose of the loan only a small percentage said that they took the loan due to illness or to cover daily expenses. 16 HIV and Poverty in Vietnam In 2005 the UNDP commissioned a case study on the household impact of HIV/AIDS in Vietnam.17 Individuals were contacted through health ser- vices in four cities; of the 129 individ- uals studied, 45 had already died of an AIDS-related illness and 84 were PLHIV. A few individuals were from the same household so that a total of 125 households were studied. By analyzing health care expenses the study estimated that an HIV-af- fected household in Vietnam has 13 times the expenditures as those for an average household. More than half the individuals studied had given up their job or had reduced income since being infected. About 25% of the caregivers for the PLHIV had to give up a job as well. Coping strategies for the house- holds in the Vietnam study were very similar to those reported in the other studies (Table 4.5). Notably however, cu