-9554-bbec943d594d", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "18118500e1eab63261988fa4c77fb013a13c722d03b9d9c4d2382f20b937fa22"}}, "hash": "e25892599301fbaf24d668b138faa98249b40064b0a0bcd5b78fb933d3b7d9bd", "text": "for foster care 1.6 Receiving a loan from credit programs 1.6 Source: Household Impact Case Study 21 15 There was a problem with the food data for the OVC households so this graph could not be created for this topic. 16 No poverty analysis was done for Cambodia due to the difficulty of estimating the value of the food provided by the food support program. 17 Primary data from the study were not available so the findings reported here are drawn from the study report [58]. Figure 6.1 total annual amount of savings, dissavings, borrowing, and assets liquidated for HIV and non-HIV affected households, India Figure 5.2 Per capita monthly household expenditures on food by type of food and income quintile, HIV households, China Figure 7.1 Per capita income, dissavings, borrowing and assets liquidated for HIV and non-HIV affected households in rural and urban areas, India Figure 1.4 Percent of monthly household expenditures by type of expenditure, OVC and PLHA control and intervention households, Cambodia payment for health expenses, the households differed greatly by in- come quintiles (Figure 7.5). Only the poorest households reported that they sold assets to pay for healthcare costs. The use of savings increases with household income while the use of borrowing decreases. The study also analyzed household consumption expenditures to esti- mate the impact of HIV on poverty, and to project the impact of pov- erty to 2015. Regression modeling was used to estimate this impact. It found that HIV-affected households reduced consumption expenditures that they would otherwise make by between 37% (for the poor- est households) and 42% (for the wealthiest households). With regard to poverty, they found that all house- holds below the wealthiest quintile (in other words, 80% of households) would fall below the poverty line as a result of the income and expendi- ture effects of HIV. In the aggregate, they found that 126,000 additional persons fell below the poverty line in 2004 due to HIV and that an ad- ditional 404,000 would fall into pov- erty by 2015. A Preliminary Study of the Impact of HIV on Poverty and Food Security Among HIV-affected Households in Asia 22 Figure 2a.4 Percent of monthly household expenditures on food by expenditure quintile, OVC control and intervention households, Cambodia Figure 2b.4 Percent of monthly household expenditures on food by expenditure quintile, PLHA control and intervention households, Cambodia Figure 3.4 Per capita monthly household expenditures by type of expenditure, OVC and PLHA control and intervention households, Cambodia Figure 5.4 Per capita household expenditures on food by type of food and income quintile, OVC and PLHA control and intervention households, Cambodia Figure 7.5 Sources used for healthcare expenses by income quintile, Vietnam 23 Chapter Five diScuSSion & concluSionS The findings from this study, while providing greater understanding of the situation of HIV-affected house- holds in Asia, also reveal important gaps in the information needed to present a full picture of the issues. Among the most obvious of these is the lack of good quality longitu- dinal data on the impact of HIV on households. While several studies have attempted to simulate the im- pact on poverty of increased food prices, and some have estimated the impact on poverty of HIV, no study has followed households over time to see how they react to changing economic conditions. This need is urgent as we have already entered uncertain economic times, and pol- icy makers are still debating how to respond to global food needs and other aspects of the economic cri- ses. Given the complexity of eco- nomic forces at the present time, it is particularly important to observe household responses directly rath- er than to attempt to simulate the various factors at play. At the same time, Asian govern- ments have responded in a vari- ety of ways to meet the needs of PLHIV and their households. Some of the household studies discussed here, such as the Cambodia study, attempt to directly measure the impact of these programs on the household economy, but such in- formation is scarce. It is important to see the impact of these programs over time, especially as govern- ments change rapidly as do health policies under changing economic conditions. Aid programs are also likely to undergo massive changes in the coming months and years.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "011c00fa-6a3b-4076-9554-bbec943d594d": {"__data__": {"id_": "011c00fa-6a3b-4076-9554-bbec943d594d", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "A Preliminary Study of the Impact of HIV on Poverty and Food Security Among HIV-affected Households in Asia", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "2b81851690e96686c0f899059d301e50aee5fed3a4c5bc87eecab3bbd9809776"}, "2": {"node_id": "c9d20eeb-d48f-4f1b-8d22-69095ad7c0d0", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "e25892599301fbaf24d668b138faa98249b40064b0a0bcd5b78fb933d3b7d9bd"}}, "hash": "18118500e1eab63261988fa4c77fb013a13c722d03b9d9c4d2382f20b937fa22", "text": "Aid programs are also likely to undergo massive changes in the coming months and years. Programs addressing health\u2014 including antiretroviral treatment, care and support including psy- chosocial support, health insur- ance schemes, and other medical services\u2014as well as food support and financial assistance programs should be examined. More detail is also needed on the impact of antiretroviral treatment on households in Asia. A few stud- ies have detailed this in Africa", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "e1200010-c37a-447c-aed4-d9c95b2b240d": {"__data__": {"id_": "e1200010-c37a-447c-aed4-d9c95b2b240d", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "A Preliminary Study of the Impact of HIV on Poverty and Food Security Among HIV-affected Households in Asia", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "943e4edc28e51a339eec66b9a0ba0682b12e5665f31fd529fe7b1d3df07dbb1c"}, "3": {"node_id": "ac651b47-0456-4d81-a017-1522e38c4ada", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "2d2f0f21a43b8d7bd8476619c81e3b23ead4ccb5f16c9cc3c6c47ba0d286b65a"}}, "hash": "0781f7bb11b564a1559b617e966f5d2881df9ac917fb4a58766ff0e0d11bb15b", "text": "the response has differed in Asia, as has the response to the epidemic in general. It is particularly urgent to link information about nutri- tion and food assistance programs A Preliminary Study of the Impact of HIV on Poverty and Food Security Among HIV-affected Households in Asia 24 with antiretroviral treatment as the knowledge base in this area is not well established. Although it was not addressed in this paper, the issue of the house- hold economy, food security and risk behavior has also not been ex- amined in Asia. If possible, migra- tion and mobility in and out of the household should be part of this fo- cus. The topic should be linked with changes in household structure and family relationships that occur with food insecurity and the loss of family members from HIV. It should be noted that several of the data- sets examined in this paper include rich information on this topic that has not yet been explored\u2014for ex- ample, on differences in household structure between HIV- and non- HIV households, on remittances in and out of the household, and on mobility of household members. As part of this research, attention should be paid to include the long- term impacts of HIV as part of study designs. Most of the studies to-date have been cross-sectional, mean- ing that they provide a snapshot in time of households with a PLHIV member at different stages of the disease. By analyzing how house- holds react to different stages of illness and death and often volatile economic circumstances, programs can be better designed to deal with varying needs. Kongsin [34, 35, 36] has already done important work in this area. An important topic that has not been sufficiently investigated in Asia is that of how agricultural and other livelihood systems interact with the HIV household, particu- larly with regard to food produc- tion. Studies that have been con- ducted in African settings such as Bukusuba et al. (2007), Hilhorst et al. (2006) and Mikael (2004) provide models for this [14, 28, 40]. Several of the studies cited here have made valuable suggestions that should be noted. Naidu and Harris (2005) call for multidisci- plinary studies on these topics, as many previous studies have tended to be narrowly focused on only one aspect of the issues [42]. Booysen and Arntz (2003) advocate for more systematic study designs, includ- ing more detailed reporting on methods, that can be used to make broader and more generalized con- clusions and recommendations. Mixed methods would also greatly contribute to a richer understand- ing of the issues [13]. Finally Mu- tangadura et al. (1999) advocate in- cluding community level factors in studies of the household economy as many households rely on a wider circle of support [41]. Conclusions This paper has attempted to review the literature on the economy of the HIV-affected household and to explore the potential impact of in- creased food prices using existing studies. Part of the purpose of this exercise was to investigate gaps in the research for Asia, particularly with the rapidly shifting economic forces that are currently affecting the world today. Secondary analysis of five stud- ies has revealed that HIV-affected households face substantial medi- cal expenses, which they often fulfill using money that would oth- erwise be used for food. We have also seen that the quality as well as the quantity of food is affected in these households, as less money is available for sources of protein and nutrient-rich fruits and vegetables. This is a particularly worrisome sit- uation given the need for PLHIV to receive adequate nutrition particu- larly those receiving antiretroviral treatment. The findings of the Cambodia study reveal that food supplemen- tation programs may be an impor- tant contribution to HIV-affected households. The recently conduct- ed studies in India and China also show evidence that the food situ- ation is less severe for households with free antiretroviral drugs avail- able, in comparison to the high medical expenditures reported by Thai households in the 1999 study. While it is beyond the scope of this paper to comprehensively analyze the impact of food programs for HIV-affected households in Asia and the Pacific, it is worth noting that many organizations have initi- ated interventions in this area. The World Food Programme (WFP) pro- vides food support to households in Cambodia and Myanmar caring for chronically ill PLWHA.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "ac651b47-0456-4d81-a017-1522e38c4ada": {"__data__": {"id_": "ac651b47-0456-4d81-a017-1522e38c4ada", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/preliminary-study-impact-hiv-poverty-and-food-security-among-hiv-affected-households-asia", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "A Preliminary Study of the Impact 