ithout; from each district 150 households with recent chronic illness or death, 150 without HIV (N=300) Non-HIV (N=300)18 Vietnam Mid - 2003 Case study approach; households iden- tified from hospitals in four cities (N=125) 18 While the full sample in the Thailand study included 600 households, a 50% sample of the data (300 households) was provided for this analysis.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "66f89c73-9f7e-479f-bc84-7c8bb04edf66": {"__data__": {"id_": "66f89c73-9f7e-479f-bc84-7c8bb04edf66", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/regional-assessment-sex-trafficking-and-sti/hiv-southeast-asia-connections-between-sexual-exploitation-violence-and-sexual", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "A Regional Assessment of Sex Trafficking and STI/HIV in Southeast Asia: Connections between Sexual Exploitation, Violence and Sexual Risk", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/regional-assessment-sex-trafficking-and-sti/hiv-southeast-asia-connections-between-sexual-exploitation-violence-and-sexual", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "bcb5779f6bba68973dadcbb84eaf2b1422d63b6fde4724d9d0a226d671ed1abd"}, "3": {"node_id": "75da9677-2c96-4a80-bf9f-55c853fbab72", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/regional-assessment-sex-trafficking-and-sti/hiv-southeast-asia-connections-between-sexual-exploitation-violence-and-sexual", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "cd02d73e027ccc879d64c428f27991916879bfdab4bef2c7f6bf1ed70848b02d"}}, "hash": "5054b889a4604fbb9b7be829957b8801a31b8e092b36d268e223069d60ad561f", "text": "Sex Trafficking and STI/HIV in Southeast Asia: Connections between Sexual Exploitation, Violence and Sexual Risk Sex Trafficking and STI/HIV in Southeast Asia: Connections between Sexual Exploitation, Violence and Sexual Risk A Regional Assessment of Sex Trafficking and STI/HIV in Southeast Asia: Connections between Sexual Exploitation, Violence and Sexual Risk Jay G. Silverman, PhD Michele R. Decker, ScD Heather L. McCauley, MS Katelyn P. Mack 1Harvard School of Public Health (Boston, MA USA) Sex Trafficking and STI/HIV in Southeast Asia: Connections between Sexual Exploitation, Violence and Sexual Risk This quantitative research study on the issue of sex trafficking and HIV in Southeast Asia was undertaken by UNDP Regional HIV and Development Programme, together with the Harvard School of Public Health. The study was commissioned to the principal researchers and authors Dr. Jay Silverman and Dr. Michele Decker from the Harvard School of Public Health and covers three countries in the Southeast Asian Region, namely Cambodia, Indonesia and Thailand. The publication benefited immensely from technical reviews and inputs from Asia Pacific country offices, UNDP headquarters, Regional UN agencies and the UNDP Regional Centre in Colombo. In particular, we would like to acknowledge the contributions of: Katherine Moriarty and Rany Pen (UNDP Cambodia), Susana Fried (BDP, NY), Matt Friedman (UNIAP Thailand), Gary Lewis, Martin Fowke, Anne Bergenstrom and the regional team (UNODC Regional Centre, Thailand), and Azrul Mohd Khalib (UNAIDS and UNDP Malaysia). We are grateful to each of the researchers, who conducted the country studies and analysis, which constitute the basis for this publication: Dr. Jay Silverman, Dr. Michele Decker, Heather L. McCauley MS, and Katelyn P. Mack of Harvard University. Our special thanks are extended to Dr Jay Silverman, who led the research team, and authored the written work for this publication with the help of his team. The final report was prepared under the overall guidance and supervision of Caitlin Wiesen with substantial contributions from Kazuyuki Uji, Pramod Kumar, Marta Vallejo, Revati Chawla, Nashida Sattar, Mini John, Tiruni Yasaratne, and Kishanthani Paramjothy. We wish to thank Yumiko Yamamoto from the Trade & Investment team within the Regional Centre Colombo, who provided valuable peer review comments. We gratefully acknowledge the leadership support provided by Nicholas Rosellini and Omar Noman for undertaking the study. We would like to acknowledge with gratitude the Government of Japan for their financial assistance which made this study possible as well as their commitment to addressing the issues of trafficking and HIV in the region. The views and conclusions expressed in this report are those of its authors and do not necessarily reflect positions of UNDP, its member governments, or other collaborating or sponsoring institutions. It is our hope that this study will contribute to greater dialogue on issues of sex trafficking and HIV and more effective responses that address the health, well being and safety of sex-trafficked women and girls. Caitlin Wiesen-Antin Regional HIV/AIDS Practice Leader & Programme Coordinator, Asia & Pacific UNDP Regional Centre Colombo, Sri Lanka ACKNOWLEDGEMENTS Sex Trafficking and STI/HIV in Southeast Asia: Connections between Sexual Exploitation, Violence and Sexual Risk The lack of evidence has been one of the critical missing links to discuss, explore and act upon the nexus between HIV and human trafficking. Heightened HIV risk of girls and women trafficked for sexual exploitation is often intuitively perceived. However, the paucity of systematic research and evidence on the linkage has deterred informed discussions on the subject. It may have also contributed to the absence of coordination and sometimes even the development of dissociation among stakeholders working on HIV prevention, human trafficking and the empowerment of sex workers, both at policy and programmatic levels. In an effort to strengthen Asia\u2019s knowledge base on the subject for initiating dialogue and collective action, UNDP Regional HIV and Development Programme for Asia and the Pacific commissioned this Southeast Asian multi-country research. It is built upon a series of South Asian studies on HIV vulnerability of sex trafficked girls and women conducted by Dr. Jay Silverman and Dr.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "75da9677-2c96-4a80-bf9f-55c853fbab72": {"__data__": {"id_": "75da9677-2c96-4a80-bf9f-55c853fbab72", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/regional-assessment-sex-trafficking-and-sti/hiv-southeast-asia-connections-between-sexual-exploitation-violence-and-sexual", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "A Regional Assessment of Sex Trafficking and STI/HIV in Southeast Asia: Connections between Sexual Exploitation, Violence and Sexual Risk", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/regional-assessment-sex-trafficking-and-sti/hiv-southeast-asia-connections-between-sexual-exploitation-violence-and-sexual", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "bcb5779f6bba68973dadcbb84eaf2b1422d63b6fde4724d9d0a226d671ed1abd"}, "2": {"node_id": "66f89c73-9f7e-479f-bc84-7c8bb04edf66", "node_type": null, "metadata